Translation: # 2010 Asian Men's Youth Handball Championship

The 2010 Asian Men's Youth Handball Championship was the 8th edition of the championship, held in Fujairah, United Arab Emirates from 20 to 27 August 2010. It acted as the Asian qualifying tournament for the 2011 Men's Youth World Handball Championship.

Qatar won the tournament for the first time, defeating South Korea in the final.

## References

Asian Men's Youth Handball Championship
Asian
Handball

The district contains all of Portland west of the Willamette River (Northwest, Southwest, and South sextants) as well as a small area on the east side including three neighborhoods.\n\nThe district contains the neighborhoods of Arlington Heights, Arnold Creek, Ashcreek, Bridlemile (including Glencullen), Collins View, Crestwood, Downtown, Eastmoreland, Far Southwest, Forest Park, Goose Hollow, Hayhurst (including Vermont Hills), Hillsdale, Hillside, Homestead, Linnton, Maplewood, Markham, Marshall Park, Multnomah (including Multnomah Village), Northwest District (including Uptown, Nob Hill, and the Alphabet Historic District), Northwest Heights, Northwest Industrial, Old Town Chinatown, Pearl District, Reed, Sellwood-Moreland, South Burlingame, South Portland (including Corbett, Fulton, Lair Hill, Terwilliger, and the Johns Landing and South Waterfront developments), Southwest Hills, Sylvan-Highlands, and West Portland Park (includes Capitol Hill).\n\nDistrict 4 is currently represented on Portland City Council by Olivia Clark, Mitch Green, and Eric Zimmerman. They were elected to two-year terms in 2024; after the 2026 election, all future terms will be four years.\n\nClark was the only member of City Council to have reached the 25% threshold for election in the first round of voting.\n\n## 2024\n\nThis district's race in the 2024 Portland City Council election was notable for having the only change in the winner due to transfers performed under the single transferable vote system. (politician)\n\nJames Murray (1834 ‚Äì 22 December 1904) was an Irish-born Australian politician.\n\nHe was born in County Tipperary to farmer James Murray and Margaret O'Brien. The family arrived in Sydney in 1841 and settled at the Hunter River. Murray was educated at Morpeth, and in 1852 he became a schoolteacher at Widden. From 1854 to 1857 he was a public servant in the Treasury, and from 1857 to 1863 he was a clerk at the Customs Department. On 21 November 1855 he married Ann Kirby, with whom he would have six children. In 1863 he became a commission agent, and in 1873 he was appointed to the Newcastle Harbour Trust.\n\nIn 1874 he was elected to the New South Wales Legislative Assembly for Northumberland. He was a supporter of Henry Parkes, and served as Minister for Justice from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Public Instruction from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Works from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Public Works from January to April 1877 and from November 1877 to December 1878, and Colonial Secretary from January to April 1877.\n\nHe was defeated in 1878, but was elected for Newcastle in 1882 and served until his defeat in 1885. Translation: # James Murray (politician)

James Murray (1834 ‚Äì 22 December 1904) was an Irish-born Australian politician.

He was born in County Tipperary to farmer James Murray and Margaret O'Brien. The family arrived in Sydney in 1841 and settled at the Hunter River. Murray was educated at Morpeth, and in 1852 he became a schoolteacher at Widden. From 1854 to 1857 he was a public servant in the Treasury, and from 1857 to 1863 he was a clerk at the Customs Department. On 21 November 1855 he married Ann Kirby, with whom he would have six children. In 1863 he became a commission agent, and in 1873 he was appointed to the Newcastle Harbour Trust.

In 1874 he was elected to the New South Wales Legislative Assembly for Northumberland. He was a supporter of Henry Parkes, and served as Minister for Justice from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Public Instruction from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Works from January to April 1877 and again from November 1877 to December 1878, Minister for Public Works from January to April 1877 and from November 1877 to December 1878, and Colonial Secretary from January to April 1877.

He was defeated in 1878, but was elected for Newcastle in 1882 and served until his defeat in 1885. He was appointed to the New South Wales Legislative Council in 1895, serving until his death at his home in Woollahra in 1904. His son, James, was also a member of parliament.

[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Epoxy molding compounds\n\nEpoxy Molding Compounds (EMC) represent a category of advanced materials utilized in electronic packaging, primarily consisting of epoxy resin, phenolic compounds, curing agent, fillers, and various additives. To safeguard electronic components against mechanical damage, contamination, and moisture, mass production techniques such as injection molding or transfer molding are typically employed to encapsulate these components within the EMC. Upon curing, the epoxy resin develops a three-dimensional network structure that exhibits superior mechanical properties as well as resistance to heat and moisture, rendering it highly effective in protecting devices from environmental factors.\n\n## History\n\nThe development of semiconductor technology commenced in the 1940s with the introduction of germanium diodes, subsequently progressing with the invention of transistors. This innovation facilitated the miniaturization of circuits and reduced power consumption, thereby catalyzing the emergence of the contemporary computer era. The packaging employed for these semiconductor devices serves to provide protection and enables their connection to printed circuit boards. Initially, the packaging technology utilized for diodes and transistors involved canned sealing. However, with advancements in passivation technology, plastic packaging methods were introduced. This plastic packaging technology has proven instrumental in enabling the mass production and cost-effective supply of semiconductor devices.\n\nThe advancement of plastic packaging technology has facilitated its extensive utilization in both consumer and industrial products. Currently, over 80% of semiconductor devices are encapsulated using epoxy molding compounds.\n\nThe advancement of semiconductor technology has consistently encountered the challenge of enhancing functionality while simultaneously reducing physical dimensions. The integration of an increasing number of functions onto semiconductor chips has resulted in a corresponding rise in both the number of pins and the overall size of the chips. Conversely, to facilitate more compact arrangements on circuit boards, there has been a trend towards miniaturization and reduction in the thickness of packaging.\n\n## Curing\n\nThe polymerization of epoxy materials can take place through two primary mechanisms: step-growth polymerization and chain-growth polymerization. In step-growth polymerization, the chemical constituents react incrementally, ultimately yielding a polymer with a high molecular weight. Conversely, chain-growth polymerization involves the successive addition of reactive sites, leading to the formation of a high molecular-weight polymer. Notably, certain curing agents, including dicyandiamide and various anhydrides, facilitate curing through intricate processes that encompass both step growth and catalytic polymerization.\n\n## Post-curing\n\nThe reactivity of monomers, specifically the quantity of reactive groups present, plays a critical role in influencing their behavior during the gelation process. Monomers characterized by high functionality tend to undergo gelation at a lower level of reaction, yet they possess an increased capacity for cross-linking. To achieve a matrix exhibiting elevated modulus and glass transition temperature, a higher degree of crosslinking is essential, which is a prerequisite for effective post-curing.\n\n## Component\n\nEpoxy encapsulation materials are a type of highly filled particulate polymer composite, comprising various components to meet the requirements for reliability, physical properties, and moldability. These components include silica, epoxy resin, hardeners, flame retardants, catalysts, and stress-relaxation additives. The raw materials are mixed at room temperature and subsequently processed in a mixing machine or roller mixer, where they are heated and blended to achieve a homogeneous mixture.\n\n## Reference\n\nMicroelectronic and microelectromechanical systems\nSemiconductor devices', 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # L'Amour Toujours

"L'Amour Toujours" (English: "Love Always") is a song by Italian singer Gigi D'Agostino. It was released in 2000 and was the lead single from his debut studio album, L'Amour Toujours. The song is D'Agostino's best known work and has been described as a "pop-trance classic".

## Music video

The music video for the song was directed by Gaetano Morbioli. It features D'Agostino and his friends in a shabby apartment, drinking and having fun, while people are dancing outside the building. The video was shot in Turin.

The 1924‚Äì25 Scottish Cup was the 47th staging of Scotland's most prestigious football knockout competition. The Cup was won by Celtic who defeated Rangers 4‚Äì0 in the final. The match was the clubs' first meeting in the final of the competition and was the first time a Scottish Cup final had been played at Hampden Park.

[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# East Gippsland United FC\n\nEast Gippsland United FC is a soccer club based in Bairnsdale, Victoria, Australia. The club was founded in 2009 and currently competes in Latrobe Valley Soccer League and are often to referred to as the Eagles.\n\nThe club was formed in order to bring high level competitive football to East Gippsland, and it focuses on representing the towns of the region, including Bairnsdale, Lakes Entrance, Paynesville, Eastwood, Wy Yung and Orbost.\n\nThe club is yet to win a senior men\'s or women\'s LVSL title but did claim the LVSL Second Division and the Nan Bosma Cup in 2023.\n\n## Efforts to start football in the region (1953‚Äì2008)\n\nAttempts to bring football to East Gippsland were a stop-start affair in the 20th century, with the first recorded team in Bairnsdale being formed in 1953. They made their debut in a game against the RAAF Soccer Club, based at the East Sale Air Force base, on November 8, 1953, at the Lucknow Recreation Reserve, on Bairnsdale\'s eastern edge.\n\nBairnsdale\'s strength was immediately obvious, as they defeated the Airmen 7-1 - despite the RAAF featuring Australian international Ralph Walker at centre-half. Bairnsdale wore Australian Rules football jerseys, loaned from the Lucknow Football Club.\n\nHowever, it wasn\'t until 1970 that Bairnsdale Soccer Club entered the Latrobe Valley Soccer League that East Gippsland was fully represented at the highest level. The club struggled in their early years, finishing third last in the first season.\n\nIn 1989, Bairnsdale Soccer Club became the name of the local Futsal club, representing East Gippsland in the indoor version of the game.\n\n## EGUFC commences, facility upgraded (2008-)\n\nEast Gippsland United\'s genesis can be found in its first \'unofficial team\' - an under-14 team which actually drew its representatives from Bairnsdale but was forced represent Sale United FC, located some 65 kilometres away.\n\nThe team that was administrated, coached and managed by the founders of EGUFC, who formally moved to start their own club as a result.\n\nEGUFC officially began in February 2009 and the club entered 3 teams (2 junior and 1 senior) in the Gippsland Soccer League (GSL).\n\nThese were teams largely assembled from participants in a 2008 summer competition, which was largely devised as a \'test event\' to gauge the demand for outdoor football in the area.\n\nSome 382 players registered for the event, far exceeding expectations and it was decided to launch an official club - East Gippsland United FC - to play home and away games in the Gippsland Soccer League a year earlier than planned.\n\nIn 2009, EGUFC finished the year with 395 registered players and it was recognised that the club had already outgrown the facilities it had been allowed to use by the East Gippsland Shire.\n\nThe club soon grew to have a Women\'s team and multiple teams across nearly all available age groups.\n\nIn 2024, EGUFC coach Dave Claridge was awarded the LVSL\'s senior men\'s coach of the year.\n\nThe club is also host to the "East Gippsland Soccer League", which sees numerous junior teams play in a competition where team names are derived from the surrounding areas.\n\nThe popularity of EGUFC meant that the club\'s Howitt Park facility - now known as The WORLD Sporting Precinct - has required significant upgrades to cater for demand, with approval for the upgrades due to be approved in mid-2025.\n\n## Club colours and badge\n\nThe club plays in blue and yellow jerseys.\n\n## Stadium\n\nThe club plays its home matches at Howitt Park, which has a capacity of 500 (with a seating capacity of 100).\n\n## Club achievements\n\n* Latrobe Valley Soccer League 2nd Division\nChampions (1): 2023\n\n* Nan Bosma Cup\nChampions (1): 2023\n\n## External links\n\n* East Gippsland United Soccer Club on FaceBook\n\nAssociation football clubs established in 2009\n2009 establishments in Australia\nSoccer clubs in Victoria (state)', 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # Jeff Hall (rower)

Jeff Hall (born 14 June 1969) is a former Australian representative rower. He is an Olympic champion, a three-time World champion and an Australian national champion.

## Club and state rowing

Hall was raised in the Melbourne suburb of Black Rock. His senior rowing was from the Melbourne University Boat Club.

Hall's state representative debut for Victoria was in the 1994 men's eight contesting the King's Cup at the Interstate Regatta within the Australian Rowing Championships. He rowed in six consecutive Victorian King's Cup eights from 1994 to 1999.

## International representative rowing

Hall's first Australian representative selection was for the 1993 World Rowing Championships in Racice where he rowed in the Australian men's eight to a fourth placing. The following year in 1994, he was selected in the Australian men's eight to compete at the World Rowing Championships in Indianapolis. That crew won Australia's first ever World Championship in men's eight rowing.

In 1995 Hall was elevated to the Australian men's sweep-oared coxless four with his Victorian teammates Robert Jahrling, Mike McKay and Kerry Hore. That crew won their heat, placed third in the semi-final and then won the gold medal in the final at the 1995 World Rowing Championships in Tampere. In 1996 at the World Rowing Championships in Motherwell, Scotland, the Australian sweep-oared coxless four of Hall, McKay, Jahrling and Stephen Hawkins won their heat and semi-final and then took the gold medal in the final.

At the 1996 Atlanta Olympics the Australian men's eight, with Hall at stroke, won the gold medal. They won their heat and semi-final and took the gold in the final.

In 1997 Hall was again selected in the Australian men's sweep-oared coxless four. They placed fourth in the final at the World Rowing Championships in Aiguebelette. Hall's final Australian representative appearance was in 1998 when he was selected in the Australian eight to race at the World Rowing Championships in Cologne. That crew placed fourth in the final.

## Coaching

Hall is a qualified sports scientist and has worked as a rowing coach. He has coached at the Melbourne University Boat Club and was the women's head coach at the Mercantile Rowing Club between 2007 and 2010. He was the Australian women's sweep coach for the 2010 World Rowing Championships and the Australian women's head coach for the 2011 World Rowing Championships.

## Post rowing

Hall has a Bachelor of Medical Science and a Master of Sports Science from the University of Melbourne. He has worked as a sports scientist and lecturer at the Australian Institute of Sport, and as a consultant for the Australian Olympic Committee and the Australian Institute of Sport.

## Recognition

In 2015 Hall was inducted into the Victorian Honour Roll of Champion Women and Men.

Translation: # 2021‚Äì22 UMass Minutemen basketball team

The 2021‚Äì22 UMass Minutemen basketball team represented the University of Massachusetts Amherst during the 2021‚Äì22 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The Minutemen, led by third-year head coach Frank Martin, played their home games at the William D. Mullins Memorial Center in Amherst, Massachusetts as members of the Atlantic 10 Conference.

## Previous season

The Minutemen finished the 2020‚Äì21 season 6‚Äì16, 3‚Äì13 in A-10 play to finish in 12th place. They were defeated by George Mason in the first round of the A-10 tournament.

[{'content': "Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Barry Dunaway\n\nBarry Dunaway is an American rock bassist, vocalist, and composer. His professional music career dates back to his early 1970s roles in groups Cheyenne and Bittersweet, and he performed with bands fronted by artists Pat Travers, Joe Lynn Turner, and Yngwie Malmsteen in the 1980s. Dunaway has played bass guitar in the band 38 Special since 2013.\n\n## Early life\n\nDunaway was born to James Melvin Dunaway and Irma May Provost, both of whom served in the United States Coast Guard. At the age of 15 Dunaway played with his brother Don Oja-Dunaway in the bands Cheyenne and Bittersweet, performing at local venues like Raven Gallery and Bistro. Dunaway and his brother Don eventually formed the band Chuffa with their sister Sharon on vocals and keyboards. Separately from his family, Dunaway played bass guitar in the Atlanta folk rock group Silverman at age 17.\n\n## 1970s\n\nIn 1974, Dunaway joined the Dawson Boys, a country rock music band based in Atlanta and fronted by Ed and Bob Dawson. Dunaway played bass guitar on the group‚Äôs 1976 album These Summer Nights. Writing for the Columbia Record, Pat Berman noted ‚Äúfolk, pop, blues and occasional jazz‚Äù influences in the songs on the effort. Dunaway also played with the Atlanta, Georgia rock group Magic Cat in the late 1970s.\n\n## 1980‚Äì1999\n\nIn 1980, Dunaway joined the Atlanta band Whiteface, replacing their previous bassist Kyle Henderson. He helped write some songs on their 1981 sophomore album Change of Face on Mercury Records. The same year, Dunaway recorded on Paul Davis‚Äô album Cool Night on Arista Records before going on to perform with the band Bareback, also formed by Whiteface cofounder Doug Bare.\n\nDunaway was playing with Warner Records-signed band Riggs in 1982 when he and Riggs founder Jerry Riggs joined the band of rock musician Pat Travers. Dunaway contributed to Travers' 1984 album Hot Shot on Polydor Records as well as recording the band‚Äôs live album King Biscuit Flower Hour. During the mid-1980s, he also toured with Rainbow frontman Joe Lynn Turner in support of his 1985 album Rescue You, and he appeared alongside the rest of Turner‚Äôs band in the 1986 film Blue de Ville starring Jennifer Runyon.\n\nDunaway began playing with Yngwie Malmsteen in 1988. In conversation with Modern Drummer, drummer Anders Johansson credited Dunaway with helping steer Malmsteen‚Äôs classical-inspired style of heavy metal in a more practical direction for a rock band. Dunaway also recorded on numerous of Malmsteen‚Äôs albums, including Trial by Fire: Live in Leningrad in 1989, Facing the Animal in 1997, the 1998 effort Live!!, and 1999's Alchemy.\n\nDunaway joined the band Saraya as bassist for their album When The Blackbird Sings‚Ä¶, which came out on Polydor Records in 1991. He also performed and recorded with St. Augustine band Kingpins‚Äô 1999 album Kings and Things.\n\n## 2000s\n\nIn 2004-06 Dunaway played bass for the band Survivor, contributing to their 2006 album Reach. Toward the end of the 2000s, he performed with the band Rock and Pop Masters, which included rotating libe up of one-time members of bands like Survivor, Elton John, Loverboy, John Cafferty & The Beaver Brown Band, Santana, Edgar Winter, Atlanta Rhythm Section, The Young Rascals, Deep Purple, Sass Jordan, Kool & The Gang, Hall & Oates and Orleans. Around the same time, he took the stage at Rock & Pop Masters, a band whose rotating lineup featured former Foreigner and Ambrosia members. He also played with the supergroup Voices of Classic Rock, featuring singers from Loverboy, Deep Purple, Toto and Jefferson Starship.\n\n## With 38 Special\n\nDunaway was recruited to play bass for the rock band 38 Special by founding member Don Barnes, who knew of Dunaway because of his involvement with Rock & Pop Masters. In conversation with former MTV video jockey Alan Hunter, Dunaway said that he initially filled in for Larry Junstrom while he had knee surgery in 2011 but then joined the band full time by 2013.\n\nBarnes has said that Dunaway has helped reinvigorate 38 Special, which has been active since 1977 despite lineup changes over the years. Dunaway still performs with the band as of 2025, making it his longest stint as bassist with a single group.\n\n## Discography\n\nDawson Boys\n\n* These Summer Nights (1976)\n\nBob Bakert\n\n* Bob Bakert (1977)\n\nPaul Davis\n\n* Cool Night (1981)\n\nEd Raetzloff\n\n* Drivin Wheels (1981)\n\nWhiteface\n\n* Change Of Face (1981)\n\nJames Anderson\n\n* Strangest Feeling (1982)\n\nMajor Lance\n\n* The Major's Back (1983)\n\nPat Travers\n\n* Hot Shot (1984)\n\n* School of Hard Knocks (1989)\n\n* King Biscuit Flower Hour (1997)\n\n* From the Front Row Live (2001)\n\n* Le Concert du Siecle (2001)\n\nYngwie J. Malmsteen's Rising Force\n\n* Odyssey Tour (1988)\n\n* Alchemy (1999)\n\n* Lost In A Dream (2007)\n\n* First Odyssey (2007)\n\n* Now Your Ships Are Burned: The Polydor Years 1984-1990 (2004)\n\nYngwie Malmsteen\n\n* Trial By Fire: Live In Leningrad (1989)\n\n* The Yngwie Malmsteen Collection (1991)\n\n* Facing The Animal (1997)\n\n* Live!! outputs=[CompletionOutput(index=0, text='# List of accolades received by The Hunger Games (film series)\n\nThe Hunger Games is a media franchise based on the series of dystopian novels by Suzanne Collins. The series, which began in 2008 with The Hunger Games, follows the adventures of Katniss Everdeen, a teenage girl in the fictional dystopian nation of Panem. The series is set in a post-apocalyptic North America where the nation of Panem, an oligarchy consisting of a wealthy Capitol and twelve outlying districts, is ruled by a totalitarian government. Each year, the Capitol holds a televised event called the Hunger Games, in which one boy and one girl between the ages of twelve and eighteen from each of the twelve districts are selected by lottery to compete in a fight to the death.\n\nThe franchise consists of four films, and has grossed over $3 billion at the box office, making it the 16th highest-grossing film series. The film series has received 72 award wins and 182 nominations.\n\n## \'\'The Hunger Games\'\' (2012)\n\nThe Hunger Games is a 2012 American dystopian adventure film directed by Gary Ross, and written by Ross, Billy Ray, and Collins. It is based on the 2008 novel of the same name by Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence as Katniss Everdeen, with Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Lenny Kravitz, and Donald Sutherland. Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss as she volunteers to take her sister\'s place in the Hunger Games, a fight to the death between children from each of the twelve districts in the nation.\n\nThe Hunger Games received positive reviews from critics, who praised the lead performances, production values and ambition. It won 31 awards out of 139 nominations.\n\n## \'\'The Hunger Games: Catching Fire\'\' (2013)\n\nThe Hunger Games: Catching Fire is a 2013 American dystopian adventure film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Simon Beaufoy and Michael DeBruyn. It is based on the 2009 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Lenny Kravitz, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Jeffrey Wright, and Donald Sutherland. It is the sequel to The Hunger Games (2012) and the second installment in The Hunger Games film series. Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen, who, with fellow District 12 tribute Peeta Mellark, wins the 74th annual Hunger Games. However, Katniss\'s defiance of the Capitol during the Games and her subsequent actions with Peeta are seen as a threat by the Capitol\'s President Snow. As punishment, Katniss is forced to compete in a special "Quarter Quell" Hunger Games, along with previous victors from the twelve districts.\n\nThe Hunger Games: Catching Fire received positive reviews from critics, who praised the performances, action sequences, and visual effects. It won 17 awards out of 69 nominations.\n\n## \'\'The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1\'\' (2014)\n\nThe Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1 is a 2014 American dystopian adventure film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Peter Craig. It is based on the 2010 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Julianne Moore, Jeffrey Wright, Philip Seymour Hoffman, and Donald Sutherland. It is the third installment in The Hunger Games film series and the first part in a two-part adaptation of the novel.\n\nSet in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen, who has been rescued from the arena of the 75th Annual Hunger Games by the rebels of District 13, led by President Alma Coin. Katniss becomes the symbol of the rebellion and is thrust into the role of "Mockingjay" by the rebels. Katniss and her friends, Gale, Finnick, and Peeta, are sent on missions to boost the morale of the districts. However, Peeta is captured by the Capitol and is brainwashed to become a propaganda tool for President Snow.\n\nThe Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1 received positive reviews from critics, who praised the film\'s performances, direction, and action sequences. It won 11 awards out of 41 nominations.\n\n## \'\'The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2\'\' (2015)\n\nThe Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2 is a 2015 American dystopian action film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Peter Craig. It is based on the 2010 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Julianne Moore, Natalie Dormer, Sam Claflin, Jeffrey Wright, and Donald Sutherland. It is the fourth and final installment in The Hunger Games film series and the second part in a two-part adaptation of the novel.\n\nSet in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen as she leads the rebellion against the Capitol. Katniss and her friends, Gale, Finnick, and Peeta, continue their missions to boost the morale of the districts. However, Peeta is captured by the Capitol and is brainwashed to become a propaganda tool for President Snow. As the war escalates, Katniss must make difficult choices and face her fears in order to defeat the Capitol and bring peace to Panem.\n\nThe Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2 received positive reviews from critics, who praised the film\'s performances, direction, and action sequences. It won 10 awards out of 35 nominations.\n\n## \'\'The Hunger Games\'\' (2012)\n\n|-\n| rowspan="11" | 2013\n| rowspan="11" | The Hunger Games\n| rowspan="3" | Teen Choice Awards\n| Choice Movie: Translation: # List of accolades received by The Hunger Games (film series)

The Hunger Games is a media franchise based on the series of dystopian novels by Suzanne Collins. The series, which began in 2008 with The Hunger Games, follows the adventures of Katniss Everdeen, a teenage girl in the fictional dystopian nation of Panem. The series is set in a post-apocalyptic North America where the nation of Panem, an oligarchy consisting of a wealthy Capitol and twelve outlying districts, is ruled by a totalitarian government. Each year, the Capitol holds a televised event called the Hunger Games, in which one boy and one girl between the ages of twelve and eighteen from each of the twelve districts are selected by lottery to compete in a fight to the death.

The franchise consists of four films, and has grossed over $3 billion at the box office, making it the 16th highest-grossing film series. The film series has received 72 award wins and 182 nominations.

## ''The Hunger Games'' (2012)

The Hunger Games is a 2012 American dystopian adventure film directed by Gary Ross, and written by Ross, Billy Ray, and Collins. It is based on the 2008 novel of the same name by Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence as Katniss Everdeen, with Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Lenny Kravitz, and Donald Sutherland. Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss as she volunteers to take her sister's place in the Hunger Games, a fight to the death between children from each of the twelve districts in the nation.

The Hunger Games received positive reviews from critics, who praised the lead performances, production values and ambition. It won 31 awards out of 139 nominations.

## ''The Hunger Games: Catching Fire'' (2013)

The Hunger Games: Catching Fire is a 2013 American dystopian adventure film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Simon Beaufoy and Michael DeBruyn. It is based on the 2009 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Lenny Kravitz, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Jeffrey Wright, and Donald Sutherland. It is the sequel to The Hunger Games (2012) and the second installment in The Hunger Games film series. Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen, who, with fellow District 12 tribute Peeta Mellark, wins the 74th annual Hunger Games. However, Katniss's defiance of the Capitol during the Games and her subsequent actions with Peeta are seen as a threat by the Capitol's President Snow. As punishment, Katniss is forced to compete in a special "Quarter Quell" Hunger Games, along with previous victors from the twelve districts.

The Hunger Games: Catching Fire received positive reviews from critics, who praised the performances, action sequences, and visual effects. It won 17 awards out of 69 nominations.

## ''The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1'' (2014)

The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1 is a 2014 American dystopian adventure film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Peter Craig. It is based on the 2010 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Julianne Moore, Jeffrey Wright, Philip Seymour Hoffman, and Donald Sutherland. It is the third installment in The Hunger Games film series and the first part in a two-part adaptation of the novel.

Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen, who has been rescued from the arena of the 75th Annual Hunger Games by the rebels of District 13, led by President Alma Coin. Katniss becomes the symbol of the rebellion and is thrust into the role of "Mockingjay" by the rebels. Katniss and her friends, Gale, Finnick, and Peeta, are sent on missions to boost the morale of the districts. However, Peeta is captured by the Capitol and is brainwashed to become a propaganda tool for President Snow.

The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 1 received positive reviews from critics, who praised the film's performances, direction, and action sequences. It won 11 awards out of 41 nominations.

## ''The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2'' (2015)

The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2 is a 2015 American dystopian action film directed by Francis Lawrence and written by Peter Craig. It is based on the 2010 novel of the same name by Suzanne Collins. The film stars Jennifer Lawrence, Josh Hutcherson, Liam Hemsworth, Woody Harrelson, Elizabeth Banks, Julianne Moore, Natalie Dormer, Sam Claflin, Jeffrey Wright, and Donald Sutherland. It is the fourth and final installment in The Hunger Games film series and the second part in a two-part adaptation of the novel.

Set in a dystopian future in which North America is controlled by the totalitarian nation of Panem, the film follows Katniss Everdeen as she leads the rebellion against the Capitol. Katniss and her friends, Gale, Finnick, and Peeta, continue their missions to boost the morale of the districts. However, Peeta is captured by the Capitol and is brainwashed to become a propaganda tool for President Snow. As the war escalates, Katniss must make difficult choices and face her fears in order to defeat the Capitol and bring peace to Panem.

The Hunger Games: Mockingjay ‚Äì Part 2 received positive reviews from critics, who praised the film's performances, direction, and action sequences. It won 10 awards out of 35 nominations.

It was one of three that linked Tenochtitlan with the shores of the surrounding lakes. In 1519 it was used by conquistador Hern√°n Cort√©s to enter the city.\n\n## Modern day\n\nSince 1970, line 2 of the Mexico City Metro runs down the Calzada de Tlalpan\'s median after emerging from its underground section at San Antonio Abad station. The Xochimilco light rail continues down the Calzada after the metro\'s terminus at Tasque√±a. Both transit systems follow the right-of-way of a former tram line.\n\nFor vehicular traffic, the Calzada ends at its junction with Avenida Insurgentes in the borough of Tlalpan, where Federal Highways 95 and 95D continue south to Cuernavaca, Morelos, and beyond.\n\n## References\n\nStreets in Mexico City', 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # 1977‚Äì78 West Ham United F.C. season

The 1977‚Äì78 season was West Ham United's 59th season in the Football League and their 21st season in the First Division.

## Season summary

West Ham had a good start to the season, and were top of the First Division table in early September. However, a run of only one win in their next 12 league games saw West Ham fall down the table. They finally won again in November, and were able to climb back up to 10th in the table by the end of 1977. However, a poor run of form in the second half of the season saw them drop to 14th, just four points clear of the relegation zone.

Trevor Brooking returned to the club from Barcelona during the season, and scored 14 goals in 30 league matches.

## Final league table

P = Matches played; W = Matches won; D = Matches drawn; L = Matches lost; F = Goals for; A = Goals against; GD = Goal difference; Pts = Points

Translation: # Ephrem (disambiguation)

Ephrem is a given name and a surname. Notable people with the name include:

## Given name

* Ephrem the Syrian (c. 306‚Äì373), Syriac Christian theologian, hymnographer and writer

* Ephrem I of Cilicia (died 490), Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch from 433 to 490

* Ephrem the Younger (died 442), Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch from 491 to 442

* Ephrem of Nisibis (died 497), Syriac Orthodox Patriarch of Antioch from 476 to 497

* Ephrem I of Constantinople (died 715), Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople from 705 to 715

* Ephrem II of Constantinople (died 1046), Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople from 1034 to 1046

* Ephrem III of Constantinople (died 1191), Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople from 1190 to 1191

## Surname

* Andr√© Ephrem (born 1981), French footballer

* Joseph Ephrem (1903‚Äì1974), French politician

* Ziziphus mauritiana, known as the Indian jujube, jujube, or ber, a fruit-bearing tree in the family Rhamnaceae

## See also

* Ephrem the Confessor, a 2006 film about the life of Ephrem the Syrian

* Ephrem (crater), a lunar impact crater on the Moon
[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Ending Illegal Discrimination And Restoring Merit-Based Opportunity\n\nExecutive Order "Ending Illegal Discrimination And Restoring Merit-Based Opportunity", is an executive order signed by Donald Trump, the 47th President of the United States, on January 21, 2025. The executive order instructs federal departments not to issue contracts to private organizations that enforce diversity, equity, inclusion and accessibility (DEIA) frameworks. The order does not affect state or lower jurisdiction level DEIA related government contracting practices. It specifically prevents affirmative action from being implemented by government contractors. The order also revoked certain parts of the Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) order that was signed by Lyndon B. Johnson in 1965, as well as other orders, in terms of federal contracting jobs. The order also requests federal agencies to start an investigation on 9 publicly traded companies.\n\nMany have claimed this as being anti-minority and would decrease the likelihood of individuals in minority groups from getting a job.\n\n## Provisions\n\n* Revocation of the following executive orders and presidential memorandum:\n\n* \n* Executive Order 11246\n\n* \n* Executive Order 12898\n\n* \n* Executive Order 13583\n\n* \n* Executive Order 13672\n\n* \n* Presidential Memorandum of October 5, 2016\n\n* Direct all executive departments and agencies to eliminate any discriminatory or unlawful preferences, mandates, policies, programs, activities, guidelines, regulations, enforcement actions, consent orders, and requirements\n\n* Instruct all agencies to uphold established civil rights laws and address unlawful diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) practices in the private sector.\n\n* The federal contracting process will be simplified to improve speed and efficiency, lower costs, and ensure that federal contractors and subcontractors adhere to civil rights laws.\n\n* The Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs within the Department of Labor is directed to immediately stop:\n\n* \n* Promoting ‚Äúdiversity‚Äù\n\n* \n* Requiring federal contractors and subcontractors to implement ‚Äúaffirmative action‚Äù measures\n\n* \n* Permitting or encouraging federal contractors and subcontractors to adjust their workforce composition based on race, color, gender, sexual orientation, religion, or national origin\n\n* As outlined in Executive Order 13279 of December 12, 2002 (Equal Protection of the Laws for Faith-Based and Community Organizations), federal contractors and subcontractors must ensure that their employment, procurement, and contracting practices do not consider race, color, gender, sexual orientation, religion, or national origin in any manner that violates the nation‚Äôs civil rights laws.\n\n* The head of each agency must include necessary actions within their operations to promote in the private sector the principles of individual initiative, excellence, and hard work outlined in Section 2 of this order.\n\n* To assist in developing effective civil-rights policies for Trump adminstration, the Attorney General, within 120 days of this order, in consultation with relevant agency heads and in coordination with the Director of OMB, shall provide a report to the Assistant to the President for Domestic Policy. This report will include recommendations for enforcing federal civil-rights laws and measures to encourage the private sector to eliminate illegal discrimination and preferences, including DEI-related practices. The report will include a proposed strategic enforcement plan that identifies:\n\n* \n* Key sectors of concern under each agency‚Äôs jurisdiction;\n\n* \n* The most egregious and discriminatory DEI practitioners within each sector of concern;\n\n* \n* A detailed plan outlining specific steps to deter DEI programs or principles (whether labeled as ‚ÄúDEI‚Äù or otherwise) that involve illegal discrimination or preferences. As part of this plan, each agency will identify up to nine potential civil compliance investigations targeting publicly traded corporations, large nonprofit organizations, foundations with assets of $500 million or more, state and local bar and medical associations, and institutions of higher education with endowments exceeding $1 billion;\n\n* \n* Additional strategies to encourage the private sector to eliminate illegal DEI discrimination and preferences while ensuring compliance with federal civil-rights laws;\n\n* \n* Potential litigation for federal lawsuits, interventions, or statements of interest; and\n\n* \n* Possible regulatory actions and sub-regulatory guidance.\n\n* Within 120 days of this order, the Attorney General and the Secretary of Education shall jointly provide guidance to all state and local educational agencies that receive federal funding, as well as to all institutions of higher education that receive federal grants or participate in the federal student loan assistance program under Title IV of the Higher Education Act, 20 U.S.C. 1070 et seq. This guidance will outline the measures and practices necessary to comply with the decision in Students for Fair Admissions, Inc. v. President and Fellows of Harvard College, 600 U.S. 181 (2023).\n\n* If any part of this order, or its application to a specific person or situation, is found to be invalid, the rest of the order and its application to other individuals or circumstances will remain unaffected.\n\n* This order does not apply to lawful employment or contracting preferences for U.S. armed forces veterans or individuals protected under the Randolph-Sheppard Act, 20 U.S.C. 107 et seq.\n\n* \n* This order does not restrict state or local governments, federal contractors, or federally funded state and local educational agencies or institutions of higher education from engaging in speech protected by the First Amendment.\n\n* \n* This order does not prohibit educators at federally funded institutions of higher education from advocating for, endorsing, or promoting the employment or contracting practices prohibited by this order, as part of broader academic instruction.\n\n* Nothing in this order shall be interpreted to:\n\n* \n* Limit or alter the authority legally granted to any executive department, agency, or their leadership; or\n\n* \n* Interfere with the responsibilities of the Director of the Office of Management and Budget regarding budgetary, administrative, or legislative matters.\n\n* \n* This order shall be carried out in accordance with applicable laws and is subject to the availability of appropriations.\n\n* \n* This order does not create any rights or benefits, whether substantive or procedural, that are enforceable by any individual or entity against the United States, its departments, agencies, officers, employees, agents, or any other person.\n\n## Effects on current contracts\n\nThe order requires the government departments to review the hiring practices of businesses and organizations that have been contracted, as well as consider any remedies done after the signing of this order. Federal contractors were given 90 days from the signing of the order to stop DEIA practices. After the review, the departments are to determine whether to continue the contract with the current organization, give the contract to another party, or to cancel the contract.\n\nDue to this many organizations are worried if they might end up losing money from partially completed contracts, if the federal government were to rescind their contract. Because of this, many lawyers have suggested to contracted organizations to be in touch with a law-firm immediately.\n\n## See also\n\n* List of executive orders in the second presidency of Donald Trump\n\n## References\n\nExecutive orders of Donald Trump\nSecond presidency of Donald Trump', 'role': 'user'}]

The executive order instructs federal departments not to issue contracts to private organizations that enforce diversity, equity, inclusion and accessibility (DEIA) frameworks. The order does not affect state or lower jurisdiction level DEIA related government contracting practices. It specifically prevents affirmative action from being implemented by government contractors. The order also revoked certain parts of the Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) order that was signed by Lyndon B. Johnson in 1965, as well as other orders, in terms of federal contracting jobs. The order also requests federal agencies to start an investigation on 9 publicly traded companies.\n\nMany have claimed this as being anti-minority and would decrease the likelihood of individuals in minority groups from getting a job.\n\n## Provisions\n\n* Revocation of the following executive orders and presidential memorandum:\n\n* \n* Executive Order 11246\n\n* \n* Executive Order 12898\n\n* \n* Executive Order 13583\n\n* \n* Executive Order 13672\n\n* \n* Presidential Memorandum of October 5, 2016\n\n* Direct all executive departments and agencies to eliminate any discriminatory or unlawful preferences, mandates, policies, programs, activities, guidelines, regulations, enforcement actions, consent orders, and requirements\n\n* Instruct all agencies to uphold established civil rights laws and address unlawful diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) practices in the private sector.\n\n* The federal contracting process will be simplified to improve speed and efficiency, lower costs, and ensure that federal contractors and subcontractors adhere to civil rights laws.\n\n* The Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs within the Department of Labor is directed to immediately stop:\n\n* \n* Promoting ‚Äúdiversity‚Äù\n\n* \n* Requiring federal contractors and subcontractors to implement ‚Äúaffirmative action‚Äù measures\n\n* \n* Permitting or encouraging federal contractors and subcontractors to adjust their workforce composition based on race, color, gender, sexual orientation, religion, or national origin\n\n* As outlined in Executive Order 13279 of December 12, 2002 (Equal Protection of the Laws for Faith-Based and Community Organizations), federal contractors and subcontractors must ensure that their employment, procurement, and contracting practices do not consider race, color, gender, sexual orientation, religion, or national origin in any manner that violates the nation‚Äôs civil rights laws.\n\n* The head of each agency must include the following provisions in every contract or grant award:\n\n* \n* A clause stating that the contractor\'s or grant recipient\'s full compliance with all applicable federal anti-discrimination laws is a key factor in the government‚Äôs payment decisions, as outlined in section 3729(b)(4) of title 31, United States Code; and\n\n* \n* A clause requiring the contractor or recipient to certify that it does not run any programs promoting DEI that conflict with any applicable federal anti-discrimination laws.\n\n* The Director of the Office of Management and Budget (OMB), with support from the Attorney General as needed, shall:\n\n* \n* Review and update all government-wide processes, directives, and guidance as necessary;\n\n* \n* Remove references to DEI and DEIA principles‚Äîregardless of how they are labeled‚Äîfrom federal acquisition, contracting, grants, and financial assistance procedures to streamline these processes, enhance speed and efficiency, reduce costs, and ensure compliance with civil rights laws; and\n\n* \n* Eliminate all mandates, requirements, programs, or activities related to ‚Äúdiversity,‚Äù ‚Äúequity,‚Äù ‚Äúequitable decision-making,‚Äù ‚Äúequitable deployment of financial and technical assistance,‚Äù ‚Äúadvancing equity,‚Äù and similar concepts, as appropriate.\n\n* The heads of all agencies, with support from the Attorney General, must take all This report will include recommendations for enforcing federal civil-rights laws and measures to encourage the private sector to eliminate illegal discrimination and preferences, including DEI-related practices. outputs=[CompletionOutput(index=0, text='# John R. Quinn\n\nJohn Randolph Quinn (January 1, 1865 ‚Äì January 26, 1945) was an American lawyer and politician from New York.\n\n## Early life and education\n\nQuinn was born on January 1, 1865, in New York City, New York. He was the son of John Quinn and Jane (n√©e McCallion) Quinn. His father was a native of Ireland and a member of the Irish Republican Brotherhood.\n\nHe attended the public schools in New York City, and then St. Francis Xavier College, graduating in 1883. He then attended the College of the City of New York, graduating with an A.B. in 1885 and an A.M. in 1888. He also attended the law department of New York University, graduating with an LL.B. in 1888.\n\n## Career\n\nHe was admitted to the bar in 1888, and practiced law in New York City, first in partnership with James J. Monahan, and then by himself. He was a member of the New York State Assembly (New York Co., 22nd D.) in 1896 and 1897.\n\nHe was a member of the New York State Senate (17th D.) from 1901 to 1904, sitting in the 124th, 125th, 126th and 127th New York State Legislatures. On February 26, 1904, Quinn was appointed by Governor Odell to fill the vacancy caused by the resignation of State Senator John J. O\'Dea.\n\nHe was a delegate to the 1912 Republican National Convention, and was a member of the New York State Railroad Commission from 1912 to 1913.\n\nHe was a delegate to the 1924 Republican National Convention.\n\n## Personal life\n\nIn 1894, Quinn was married to Virginia F. Duffy (1874‚Äì1962). Virginia was the daughter of John Duffy, a prominent New York politician and judge, and Mary (n√©e McCallion) Duffy. Together, they were the parents of:\n\n* Jane Quinn (1896‚Äì1980), who married James J. Walker, the 100th Mayor of New York City, in 1919. They divorced in 1928 and she married lawyer John J. Boylan in 1929.\n\n* John R. Quinn Jr. (1897‚Äì1969), who married Alice O\'Connor, a daughter of Cornelius O\'Connor, in 1922.\n\n* Virginia Quinn (1901‚Äì1979), who married Charles E. Murphy, a son of Charles Francis Murphy, in 1924.\n\nQuinn died on January 26, 1945, at his home, 235 East 65th Street in Manhattan, New York City. He was buried at Calvary Cemetery in Woodside, Queens.\n\n## Descendants\n\nThrough his daughter Jane, he was the grandfather of John J. Boylan Jr. (1930‚Äì2018), who served as a judge on the New York Supreme Court and was the Chief Judge of the New York Court of Claims.\n\nThrough his daughter Virginia, he was the grandfather of Charles E. Murphy Jr. (1926‚Äì2012), who was the President of the New York City Board of Education from 1979 to 1983.\n\n## Sources\n\n* The New York Red Book compiled by Edgar L. Murlin (published by James B. Translation: # John R. Quinn

John Randolph Quinn (January 1, 1865 ‚Äì January 26, 1945) was an American lawyer and politician from New York.

## Early life and education

Quinn was born on January 1, 1865, in New York City, New York. He was the son of John Quinn and Jane (n√©e McCallion) Quinn. His father was a native of Ireland and a member of the Irish Republican Brotherhood.

He attended the public schools in New York City, and then St. Francis Xavier College, graduating in 1883. He then attended the College of the City of New York, graduating with an A.B. in 1885 and an A.M. in 1888. He also attended the law department of New York University, graduating with an LL.B. in 1888.

## Career

He was admitted to the bar in 1888, and practiced law in New York City, first in partnership with James J. Monahan, and then by himself. He was a member of the New York State Assembly (New York Co., 22nd D.) in 1896 and 1897.

He was a member of the New York State Senate (17th D.) from 1901 to 1904, sitting in the 124th, 125th, 126th and 127th New York State Legislatures. On February 26, 1904, Quinn was appointed by Governor Odell to fill the vacancy caused by the resignation of State Senator John J. O'Dea.

He was a delegate to the 1912 Republican National Convention, and was a member of the New York State Railroad Commission from 1912 to 1913.

He was a delegate to the 1924 Republican National Convention.

## Personal life

In 1894, Quinn was married to Virginia F. Duffy (1874‚Äì1962). Virginia was the daughter of John Duffy, a prominent New York politician and judge, and Mary (n√©e McCallion) Duffy. Together, they were the parents of:

* Jane Quinn (1896‚Äì1980), who married James J. Walker, the 100th Mayor of New York City, in 1919. They divorced in 1928 and she married lawyer John J. Boylan in 1929.

* John R. Quinn Jr. (1897‚Äì1969), who married Alice O'Connor, a daughter of Cornelius O'Connor, in 1922.

* Virginia Quinn (1901‚Äì1979), who married Charles E. Murphy, a son of Charles Francis Murphy, in 1924.

Quinn died on January 26, 1945, at his home, 235 East 65th Street in Manhattan, New York City. He was buried at Calvary Cemetery in Woodside, Queens.

## Descendants

Through his daughter Jane, he was the grandfather of John J. Boylan Jr. (1930‚Äì2018), who served as a judge on the New York Supreme Court and was the Chief Judge of the New York Court of Claims.

Through his daughter Virginia, he was the grandfather of Charles E. Murphy Jr. (1926‚Äì2012), who was the President of the New York City Board of Education from 1979 to 1983.

Translation: # 2012‚Äì13 FC Basel season

The 2012‚Äì13 season was the 124th season in the history of FC Basel. It was the 23rd consecutive season that the club played in the top flight of Swiss football.

## Pre-season

Basel started their pre-season training on 20 June 2012. The team had a training camp in B√∂nigen and played several friendly games. The first one was against local amateur club FC Thunstetten, followed by two away friendly matches against teams from Germany, against SC Freiburg and then against Bayern Munich. The final friendly was against local rivals FC St. Gallen on 14 July 2012.

## Domestic league

Basel started the league season with a 1‚Äì1 draw against Luzern. They played their first home league game on 22 July 2012 against Grasshopper Club and won 3‚Äì1. Basel ended the first half of the season as league leaders. The winter break lasted from 16 December 2012 to 22 February 2013. Basel ended the regular season in third position, eight points behind leaders Z√ºrich.

## Domestic cup

Basel entered the Swiss Cup in the third round and were drawn against FC Tuggen. They won the tie 8‚Äì0. In the fourth round, they played against FC Wil and won 2‚Äì0. In the fifth round, they were drawn against FC Z√ºrich and won 2‚Äì1. In the quarter-finals, they were drawn against Sion and won 4‚Äì3 on penalties after the game had ended 1‚Äì1 after extra time. They played Thun in the semi-final on 2 April 2013 and won 2‚Äì1.

## References

FC Basel seasons
Basel

[{'content': "Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Greg Lemke\n\nGreg Erwin Lemke is an American neuroscientist, immunologist, and author. He is Professor Emeritus at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies, where he previously held the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk chair. He was also an Adjunct Professor at the University of California San Diego.\n\nLemke has used molecular genetics to investigate the signaling networks that regulate immune system function and the development of the nervous system. His authored works have been published in academic journals, including Nature, Science, and Cell. He is the recipient of several awards, and was elected as a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 2007.\n\n## Education\n\nLemke earned his S.B. in Life Sciences from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he was a National Merit Scholar, in 1978. He was later awarded a Ph.D. in Biology from the California Institute of Technology in 1983, for work with Jeremy Brockes. He completed postdoctoral study in molecular biology with Richard Axel (Columbia University) in 1985.\n\n## Career\n\nLemke joined the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in 1985, eventually becoming Full Professor and Director of the Molecular Neurobiology Laboratory in 1995. He was awarded the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk Professorship in 2012, and was elected to three separate terms as Chair of the Salk Institute Faculty. In 2023, he was named Chief Science Officer of the Institute. He also held teaching appointments in the Department of Neuroscience at the University of California San Diego School of Medicine, beginning in 1988, eventually becoming Adjunct Professor in 1995. He founded Xetrios Therapeutics in 2009, which was later acquired by Kolltan Pharmaceuticals.\n\n## Research\n\nLemke's research spans discoveries in neurobiology and immunology, with a particular focus on receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) and their roles in cellular signaling, development, and immune regulation. His Ph.D. work identified glial growth factor (GGF), a protein critical for Schwann cell proliferation, elucidating its biochemical properties and distinguishing it from other growth factors. In his postdoctoral work with Axel, he cloned the Schwann cell gene that encodes myelin protein zero (MPZ), the major protein of the peripheral myelin sheath. He subsequently showed that MPZ is essential to the proper formation and function of this sheath. In his own lab at the Salk, he explored the intricate roles of RTKs in neural development, and in a single paper in 1991 provided the first identification of 11 of the 58 RTKs that are encoded in mammalian genomes. These novel RTKs included new members of the Eph, FGFR, and ErbB families, but also defined two entirely new RTK families. \n\nMuch of the subsequent work of the Lemke's lab has involved the genetic dissection, through the generation of mouse mutants, of the function of the novel RTKs identified in the 1991 paper. The most significant of these efforts address the ErbB, Eph, and, most notably, the TAM families. For example, he, along with his colleagues used loss-of-function mutants to show that ErbB4, a receptor for GGF and related ‚Äòneuregulins‚Äô, is essential for cardiac muscle differentiation, Schwann cell survival, and neuronal axon guidance. The absence of ErbB4 in mice resulted in lethal cardiac and neural developmental defects, establishing its critical function in these processes. With respect to neural development, his combined gain- and loss-of-function studies of the EphA3, 4, 5, and 6 receptors explored sensory nervous system mapping. These experiments showed that topographic neural connections are guided by relative EphA receptor expression levels in the retina, which dictate neuronal targeting from the eye to the brain. \n\nA significant part of Lemke's studies relate to the 'TAM' receptors ‚Äì Tyro3, Axl, and Mer. These receptors were initially 'orphans' ‚Äì in that their activating ligands were unknown. Along with his collaborators, he established that these ligands are Protein S and Gas6, the former known for its role in blood coagulation. These findings revealed a link between protease cascades, cellular signaling, and tissue development, emphasizing their broader physiological relevance. A large body of subsequent work demonstrated that TAM receptors are primarily expressed by phagocytic cells, in macrophages of the immune system and elsewhere, where they play two essential and mechanistically related roles. The first of these is the recognition and clearance of dead (apoptotic) cells, many billions of which are generated each day in the human body. The second is the inhibition of the innate immune response in macrophages and dendritic cells of the immune system, where TAM receptors were shown to mitigate hyperactivation of these antigen-presenting cells, preventing autoimmunity. The receptors function as feedback inhibitors of inflammation, tightly regulating Toll-like receptor and cytokine signaling cascades. \n\nLemke's research on TAM receptor-ligand activity in the context of phagocytosis and inflammation has contributed to advancements in understanding human health.. He delineated the fundamental molecular determinants of TAM receptor-ligand-phospholipid interaction. In later studies, he revealed that Axl and Mer are expressed by microglia, the macrophages of the brain and spinal cord, where they regulate critical microglial activities in both normal tissue homeostasis and disease. He demonstrated that the TAMs and their ligands are central regulators of microglial recognition and engulfment of amyloid beta in Alzheimer's disease.\n\n## Awards and honors\n \n\n* 1986-1990 ‚Äì Pew Scholar Award, Pew Charitable Trusts\n\n* 1987-1989 ‚Äì Basil O‚ÄôConnor Starter Scholar Award, March of Dimes\n\n* 1990-1995 ‚Äì Rita Allen Scholars Award, Rita Allen Foundation \n\n* 1994-2001 ‚Äì Javits Neuroscience Investigator Award, NIH\n\n* 2001 ‚Äì Fellow, American Association for the Advancement of Science\n\n## Selected articles\n\n* Gassmann, M., Casagranda, F., Orioli, D., Simon, H., Lai, C., Klein, R., & Lemke, G. (1995). Aberrant neural and cardiac development in mice lacking the ErbB4 neuregulin receptor. Nature, 378(6555), 390-394.\n\n* Stitt, T. N., Conn, G., Goret, M., Lai, C., Bruno, J., Radzlejewski, C., ... & Yancopoulos, G. D. (1995). The anticoagulation factor protein S and its relative, Gas6, are ligands for the Tyro 3/Axl family of receptor tyrosine kinases. Cell, 80(4), 661-670.\n\n* Lu, Q., & Lemke, G. (2001). Homeostatic regulation of the immune system by receptor tyrosine kinases of the Tyro 3 family. Science, 293(5528), 306-311.\n\n* Stefansson, H., Petursson, H., Sigurdsson, E., Steinthorsdottir, V., Bjornsdottir, S., Sigmundsson, T., ... & Stefansson, K. (2002). Neuregulin 1 and susceptibility to schizophrenia. The American Journal of Human Genetics, 71(4), 877-892.\n\n* Rothlin, C. V., Ghosh, S., Zuniga, E. I., Oldstone, M. B., & Lemke, G. (2007). TAM receptors are pleiotropic inhibitors of the innate immune response. Cell, 131(6), 1124-1136.\n\n* Fourgeaud, L., Trav√©s, P. G., Tufail, Y., Leal-Bailey, H., Lew, E. D., Burrola, P. G., ... & Lemke, G. (2016). TAM receptors regulate multiple features of microglial physiology. Nature, 532(7598), 240-244.\n\n* Huang, Y., Happonen, K. E., Burrola, P. G., O‚ÄôConnor, C., Hah, N., Huang, L., ... & Lemke, G. (2021). Microglia use TAM receptors to detect and engulf amyloid Œ≤ plaques. Nature immunology, 22(5), 586-594.\n\n## References\n\nAmerican neuroscientists\nAmerican academics\nAmerican immunologists\nMassachusetts Institute of Technology alumni\nCalifornia Institute of Technology alumni\nColumbia University alumni\nUniversity of California faculty\nSalk Institute for Biological Studies people\nLiving people", 'role': 'user'}]

V svojem doktorskem delu je identificiral glijalni rastni faktor (GGF), protein, ki je kljuƒçnega pomena za proliferacijo Schwannovih celic, in raziskal njegove biokemiƒçne lastnosti ter ga loƒçil od drugih rastnih faktorjev. V svojem podiplomskem delu z Axelom je kloniral gen Schwannovih celic, ki kodira protein niƒç (MPZ) niƒç, glavni protein periferne mielinske ovojnice. Pozneje je pokazal, da je MPZ bistven za pravilno oblikovanje in delovanje te ovojnice.\n\nV svojem laboratoriju na Salku je raziskoval zapletene vloge RTK v nevronskem razvoju in v enem ƒçlanku iz leta 1991 prvi opisal 11 od 58 RTK, ki so kodirani v sesalskih genih. Ti novi RTK so vkljuƒçevali nove ƒçlane dru≈æin Eph, FGF in ErbB, poleg tega pa so definirali tudi dve povsem novi dru≈æini RTK. Velik del nadaljnjega dela Lemkovega laboratorija je vkljuƒçeval genetski razkos RTK, identificiranih v ƒçlanku iz leta 1991, z uporabo mi≈°jih mutant. Najpomembnej≈°i med temi ≈°tudijami so raziskovali dru≈æine ErbB, Eph in ≈°e posebej TAM.\n\nNa primer, on in njegovi sodelavci so z uporabo mutant z izgubo funkcije pokazali, da je ErbB4, receptor za GGF in sorodne nevreguline, bistvenega pomena za diferenciacijo srƒçne mi≈°ice, pre≈æivetje Schwannovih celic in nevronsko usmerjanje aksonov. Odsotnost ErbB4 pri mi≈°ih je povzroƒçila smrtonosne nevronske in kardiovaskularne razvojne napake, kar je potrdilo njegovo kljuƒçno vlogo v teh procesih. Glede nevronskega razvoja so njegove skupne ≈°tudije z dobljeno in izgubljeno funkcijo EphA receptorjev 3, 4, 5 in 6 raziskale kartiranje senzoriƒçnega ≈æivƒçnega sistema. Ti eksperimenti so pokazali, da topografske nevronske povezave iz oƒçesa v mo≈ægane vodijo relativne ravni izra≈æanja EphA receptorjev v mre≈ænici, ki doloƒçajo nevronsko ciljanje.\n\nPomemben del Lemkovih ≈°tudij se nana≈°a na 'TAM' receptorje ‚Äì Tyro3, Axl in Mer. Ti receptorji so bili sprva 'sirote' ‚Äì njihovi aktivirajoƒçi ligandi so bili neznani. S sodelavci je ugotovil, da so ti ligandi protein S in Gas6, pri ƒçemer je prvi znan po svoji vlogi v koagulaciji krvi. Ti izsledki so razkrili povezavo med proteaznimi kaskadami, celiƒçno signalizacijo in tkivnim razvojem. Velik del nadaljnjega dela je pokazal, da so TAM receptorji predv#Greg Lemke\n\nGreg Erwin Lemke is an American neuroscientist, immunologist, and author. He is Professor Emeritus at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies, where he previously held the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk chair. He was also an Adjunct Professor at the University of California San Diego.\n\nLemke has used molecular genetics to investigate the signaling networks that regulate immune system function and the development of the nervous system. His authored works have been published in academic journals, including Nature, Science, and Cell. He is the recipient of several awards, and was elected as a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 2007.\n\n## Education\n\nLemke earned his S.B. in Life Sciences from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he was a National Merit Scholar, in 1978. He was later awarded a Ph.D. in Biology from the California Institute of Technology in 1983, for work with Jeremy Brockes. He completed postdoctoral study in molecular biology with Richard Axel (Columbia University) in 1985.\n\n## Career\n\nLemke joined the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in 1985, eventually becoming Full Professor and Director of the Molecular Neurobiology Laboratory in 1995. He was awarded the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk Professorship in 2012, and was elected to three separate terms as Chair of the Salk Institute Faculty. In 2023, he was named Chief Science Officer of the Institute. He also held teaching appointments in the Department of Neuroscience at the University of California San Diego School of Medicine, beginning in 1988, eventually becoming Adjunct Professor in 1995. He founded Xetrios Therapeutics in 2009, which was later acquired by Kolltan Pharmaceuticals.\n\n## Research\n\nLemke's research spans discoveries in neurobiology and immunology, with a particular focus on receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) and their roles in cellular signaling, development, and immune regulation. His Ph.D. work identified glial growth factor (GGF), a protein critical for Schwann cell proliferation, elucidating its biochemical properties and distinguishing it from other growth factors. In his postdoctoral work with Axel, he cloned the Schwann cell gene that encodes myelin protein zero (MPZ), the major protein of the peripheral myelin sheath. He subsequently showed that MPZ is essential to the proper formation and function of this sheath. In his own lab at the Salk, he explored the intricate roles of RTKs in neural development, and in a single paper in 1991 provided the first identification of 11 of the 58 RTKs that are encoded in mammalian genomes. These novel RTKs included new members of the Eph, FGFR, and ErbB families, but also defined two entirely new RTK families. \n\nMuch of the subsequent work of the Lemke's lab has involved the genetic dissection, through the generation of mouse mutants, of the function of the novel RTKs identified in the 1991 paper. The most significant of these efforts address the ErbB, Eph, and, most notably, the TAM families. For example, he, along with his colleagues used loss-of-function mutants to show that ErbB4, a receptor for GGF and related ‚Äòneuregulins‚Äô, is essential for cardiac muscle differentiation, Schwann cell survival, and neuronal axon guidance. The absence of ErbB4 in mice resulted in lethal cardiac and neural developmental defects, establishing its critical function in these processes. With respect to neural development, his combined gain- and loss-of-function studies of the EphA3, 4, 5, and 6 receptors explored sensory nervous system mapping.", token_ids=[2, 235345, 235248, 2, Translation: # #Greg Lemke

Greg Erwin Lemke je ameri≈°ki nevroznanstvenik, imunolog in avtor. Je profesor emeritus na Salkovem in≈°titutu za biolo≈°ke ≈°tudije, kjer je pred tem zasedal stolƒçek Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk. Bil je tudi gostujoƒçi profesor na Univerzi Kalifornije, San Diego.

Lemke je uporabil molekularno genetiko za raziskovanje signalnih mre≈æ, ki uravnavajo funkcijo imunskega sistema in razvoj ≈æivƒçnega sistema. Njegova avtorska dela so bila objavljena v znanstvenih revijah, kot so Nature, Science in Cell. Je prejemnik veƒç nagrad in je bil leta 2007 izvoljen za ƒçlana Ameri≈°kega zdru≈æenja za napredovanje znanosti.

## Izobra≈æevanje

Lemke je leta 1978 na Tehnolo≈°kem in≈°titutu Massachusettsa pridobil diplomo iz ≈æivljenjskih znanosti kot nacionalni ≈°tipendist. Leta 1983 je na Kalifornijskem tehnolo≈°kem in≈°titutu prejel doktorat iz biologije za delo z Jeremyjem Brockesom. Leta 1985 je opravil podiplomski ≈°tudij molekularne biologije z Richardom Axelom (Univerza Columbia).

## Kariera

Leta 1985 se je pridru≈æil Salkovemu in≈°titutu za biolo≈°ke ≈°tudije in leta 1995 postal polni profesor ter direktor laboratorija za molekularno nevrobiologijo. Leta 2012 je prejel stolƒçek Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk, leta 2023 pa je bil imenovan za glavnega znanstvenega uradnika in≈°tituta. Leta 1988 se je pridru≈æil Oddelku za nevroznanost na Medicinski fakulteti Univerze Kalifornije, San Diego, kjer je leta 1995 postal gostujoƒçi profesor. Ustanovil je Xetrios Therapeutics leta 2009, ki ga je kasneje prevzela dru≈æba Kolltan Pharmaceuticals.

## Raziskave

Lemke je raziskoval zapletene vloge receptorjev tirozin kinaz (RTK) v signalizaciji, razvoju in imunski regulaciji. V svojem doktorskem delu je identificiral glijalni rastni faktor (GGF), protein, ki je kljuƒçnega pomena za proliferacijo Schwannovih celic, in raziskal njegove biokemiƒçne lastnosti ter ga loƒçil od drugih rastnih faktorjev. V svojem podiplomskem delu z Axelom je kloniral gen Schwannovih celic, ki kodira protein niƒç (MPZ) niƒç, glavni protein periferne mielinske ovojnice. Pozneje je pokazal, da je MPZ bistven za pravilno oblikovanje in delovanje te ovojnice.

V svojem laboratoriju na Salku je raziskoval zapletene vloge RTK v nevronskem razvoju in v enem ƒçlanku iz leta 1991 prvi opisal 11 od 58 RTK, ki so kodirani v sesalskih genih. Ti novi RTK so vkljuƒçevali nove ƒçlane dru≈æin Eph, FGF in ErbB, poleg tega pa so definirali tudi dve povsem novi dru≈æini RTK. Velik del nadaljnjega dela Lemkovega laboratorija je vkljuƒçeval genetski razkos RTK, identificiranih v ƒçlanku iz leta 1991, z uporabo mi≈°jih mutant. Najpomembnej≈°i med temi ≈°tudijami so raziskovali dru≈æine ErbB, Eph in ≈°e posebej TAM.

Na primer, on in njegovi sodelavci so z uporabo mutant z izgubo funkcije pokazali, da je ErbB4, receptor za GGF in sorodne nevreguline, bistvenega pomena za diferenciacijo srƒçne mi≈°ice, pre≈æivetje Schwannovih celic in nevronsko usmerjanje aksonov. Odsotnost ErbB4 pri mi≈°ih je povzroƒçila smrtonosne nevronske in kardiovaskularne razvojne napake, kar je potrdilo njegovo kljuƒçno vlogo v teh procesih. Glede nevronskega razvoja so njegove skupne ≈°tudije z dobljeno in izgubljeno funkcijo EphA receptorjev 3, 4, 5 in 6 raziskale kartiranje senzoriƒçnega ≈æivƒçnega sistema. Ti eksperimenti so pokazali, da topografske nevronske povezave iz oƒçesa v mo≈ægane vodijo relativne ravni izra≈æanja EphA receptorjev v mre≈ænici, ki doloƒçajo nevronsko ciljanje.

Pomemben del Lemkovih ≈°tudij se nana≈°a na 'TAM' receptorje ‚Äì Tyro3, Axl in Mer. Ti receptorji so bili sprva 'sirote' ‚Äì njihovi aktivirajoƒçi ligandi so bili neznani. S sodelavci je ugotovil, da so ti ligandi protein S in Gas6, pri ƒçemer je prvi znan po svoji vlogi v koagulaciji krvi. Ti izsledki so razkrili povezavo med proteaznimi kaskadami, celiƒçno signalizacijo in tkivnim razvojem. Velik del nadaljnjega dela je pokazal, da so TAM receptorji predv#Greg Lemke

Greg Erwin Lemke is an American neuroscientist, immunologist, and author. He is Professor Emeritus at the Salk Institute for Biological Studies, where he previously held the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk chair. He was also an Adjunct Professor at the University of California San Diego.

Lemke has used molecular genetics to investigate the signaling networks that regulate immune system function and the development of the nervous system. His authored works have been published in academic journals, including Nature, Science, and Cell. He is the recipient of several awards, and was elected as a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 2007.

## Education

Lemke earned his S.B. in Life Sciences from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he was a National Merit Scholar, in 1978. He was later awarded a Ph.D. in Biology from the California Institute of Technology in 1983, for work with Jeremy Brockes. He completed postdoctoral study in molecular biology with Richard Axel (Columbia University) in 1985.

## Career

Lemke joined the Salk Institute for Biological Studies in 1985, eventually becoming Full Professor and Director of the Molecular Neurobiology Laboratory in 1995. He was awarded the Fran√ßoise Gilot-Salk Professorship in 2012, and was elected to three separate terms as Chair of the Salk Institute Faculty. In 2023, he was named Chief Science Officer of the Institute. He also held teaching appointments in the Department of Neuroscience at the University of California San Diego School of Medicine, beginning in 1988, eventually becoming Adjunct Professor in 1995. He founded Xetrios Therapeutics in 2009, which was later acquired by Kolltan Pharmaceuticals.

## Research

Lemke's research spans discoveries in neurobiology and immunology, with a particular focus on receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) and their roles in cellular signaling, development, and immune regulation. His Ph.D. work identified glial growth factor (GGF), a protein critical for Schwann cell proliferation, elucidating its biochemical properties and distinguishing it from other growth factors. In his postdoctoral work with Axel, he cloned the Schwann cell gene that encodes myelin protein zero (MPZ), the major protein of the peripheral myelin sheath. He subsequently showed that MPZ is essential to the proper formation and function of this sheath. In his own lab at the Salk, he explored the intricate roles of RTKs in neural development, and in a single paper in 1991 provided the first identification of 11 of the 58 RTKs that are encoded in mammalian genomes. These novel RTKs included new members of the Eph, FGFR, and ErbB families, but also defined two entirely new RTK families. 

Much of the subsequent work of the Lemke's lab has involved the genetic dissection, through the generation of mouse mutants, of the function of the novel RTKs identified in the 1991 paper. The most significant of these efforts address the ErbB, Eph, and, most notably, the TAM families. For example, he, along with his colleagues used loss-of-function mutants to show that ErbB4, a receptor for GGF and related ‚Äòneuregulins‚Äô, is essential for cardiac muscle differentiation, Schwann cell survival, and neuronal axon guidance. The absence of ErbB4 in mice resulted in lethal cardiac and neural developmental defects, establishing its critical function in these processes. With respect to neural development, his combined gain- and loss-of-function studies of the EphA3, 4, 5, and 6 receptors explored sensory nervous system mapping.

Division I men's basketball national champion for the 1992‚Äì93 season. Translation: # 1993 NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament

The 1993 NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament involved 64 schools playing in single-elimination play to determine the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I men's basketball national champion for the 1992‚Äì93 season. It began on March 17, 1993, and ended with the championship game on April 5 in New Orleans, Louisiana at the Louisiana Superdome. A total of 63 games were played, including a national third-place game for the first time.

North Carolina defeated rival and defending champion Michigan in the championship game 77‚Äì71 to win their third NCAA basketball championship. The Fab Five made their third straight appearance in the national championship game. The Tar Heels also became the first team to win the NCAA tournament as a #8 seed.

The tournament's officiating crew for the championship game was criticized for not calling fouls on North Carolina's players, who were alleged to have committed at least 12 goaltending violations.

This tournament is notable for the first subregional round, which was played at campus sites. The subregionals were played in the traditional regional format, with the East Regionals held at the Meadowlands Arena in East Rutherford, New Jersey, the Midwest Regionals at the Omni Coliseum in Atlanta, Georgia, the Mideast Regionals at the RCA Dome in Indianapolis, Indiana, and the West Regionals at the Tacoma Dome in Tacoma, Washington.
