## Bracket

* ‚Äì Denotes overtime period

## Notes

* This was the first NCAA tournament to use the subregional round.

* The 1993 tournament was the first time that a school in the state of Washington hosted an NCAA tournament game since the Pacific Coast Conference tournament was held in Seattle in 1959.

* This was the first of four consecutive NCAA tournaments in which a #8 seed reached the Final Four.

* This was the first of three consecutive NCAA tournaments in which a #8 seed won the national championship (1993, 1995, 1996).

* This was the first of four straight NCAA tournaments in which the champion was not a #1 seed.

* This was the first of six consecutive NCAA tournaments in which the defending champion did not make it to the Final Four.

* This was the first NCAA championship game to be played on a Monday.

* In the 1993 championship game, North Carolina defeated Michigan, 77‚Äì71. The Fab Five made their third straight appearance in the national championship game. North Carolina also became the first team to win the NCAA tournament as an #8 seed.

* For the second straight year, the championship game featured a team from the Atlantic Coast Conference (ACC) and a team from the Big Ten Conference.

* This was the first of four NCAA tournaments in which North Carolina won the championship.

* This was the first of two NCAA tournaments in which Michigan played in the championship game.

Translation: # 2022‚Äì23 in Argentine football

The 2022‚Äì23 season in Argentine football will be the 132nd season of competitive football in Argentina.

## [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 FIFA World Cup]]

Argentina won its third FIFA World Cup title by defeating France 4‚Äì2 in a penalty shootout after a 3‚Äì3 draw in the final.

## [[Argentine Primera Divisi√≥n]]

The 2022 Argentine Primera Divisi√≥n season began on 26 August 2022 and ended on 28 May 2023.

## [[Primera Nacional]]

The 2022 Primera Nacional season began on 16 September 2022 and ended on 28 May 2023.

## [[Primera B Metropolitana]]

The 2022 Primera B Metropolitana season began on 20 August 2022 and ended on 21 May 2023.

## [[Primera B de Santiago del Estero]]

The 2022 Primera B de Santiago del Estero season began on 20 August 2022 and ended on 21 May 2023.

## Primera D Metropolitana

The 2022 Primera D Metropolitana season began on 6 August 2022 and ended on 21 May 2023.

## [[Torneo Federal A]]

The 2022 Torneo Federal A season began on 25 September 2022 and ended on 21 May 2023.

## [[Torneo Regional Federal]]

The 2022 Torneo Regional Federal Amateur season began on 25 September 2022 and ended on 21 May 2023.

## [[Copa Argentina]]

The 2022 Copa Argentina season began on 18 March 2022 and ended on 10 June 2023.

## [[Supercopa Argentina]]

The 2023 Supercopa Argentina was held on 22 January 2023.

[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# 2020 Hong Kong Garrison helicopter crash\n\nA military helicopter of Hong Kong Garrison of Chinese People\'s Liberation Army crashed in Tai Lam Country Park, Hong Kong on 30 March 2020 during a flight training operation, reportedly killing four. The news was only confirmed a day later but no information was released regarding the crew. This is the first recorded aircraft accident involving the Chinese troops in Hong Kong since handover, and raised speculation on the details.\n\n## Accident\n\nAccording to the government, which received notification from the garrison, the helicopter was conducting flight training operation in the area of the Tai Lam Country Park in that afternoon. Villagers in Chuen Lung who witnessed the crash said there were heavy fog when the helicopter is believed to have crashed into an electricity transmission tower by accident. The chopper\'s noise stopped after explosions were heard, but no smoke or fire could be seen. The lost helicopter is believed to be a Harbin Z-9 (no. 6202).\n\nCLP Group confirmed a voltage dip incident at 4:48\xa0p.m. at a 400kV overhead line power cable connecting Lung Kwu Tan and Sha Tin which lasted for less than 0.1 seconds. The fire service received 42 reports of lift malfunction across the city within 15 minutes after the incident, while Chuen Lung residents also reported a sudden loss of electricity. Photos showed the tower and parts of the cable were damaged.\n\nA dozen of military vehicles and large group of soldiers were spotted by nearby Lui Kung Tin villagers soon after the accident. A number of helicopter flew near the location but turned away likely because of the weather condition. According to the villagers and hikers, at 7 a.m. on the next day more than a hundred military personnel, along with many police officers, entered Tai Lam Country Park via Lui Kung Tin. Some had shovels and other tools in their hands. By 9 a.m. the site was sealed off by the police and the garrison. Witnesses said a senior soldier from Hong Kong Garrison claimed there was a military exercise for the large presence of soldiers. The officers stayed for hours and remained at the crash site after 2 p.m., while CLP maintenance vehicles also travelled uphill afterwards.\n\n## Reaction\n\nThe government confirmed the news after 8 p.m. through press release, more than 27 hours after the accident. The Chinese statement described it as a crash but the English version termed "accident". Neither provided details about what had happened apart from no ground injuries.... A notification was received from the Chinese People\'s Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison (the Garrison) today to inform the Security Bureau of an accident involving a helicopter of the Garrison which occurred in the afternoon of March 30 during the Garrison\'s flight training operation conducted in the area of the Tai Lam Country Park. The incident did not involve any injury to people or damage to residences. The Garrison is handling and investigating the incident in accordance with the Garrison Law. The Security Bureau will continue to liaise with the Garrison on the incident.The fire service said they have no relevant record on handling a helicopter incident in Tai Lam.\n\nThe pro-democracy camp urged for transparency in this event. Eddie Chu, who was one of the first public figures to break the news, demanded the Security Bureau to reveal more details on the most serious accident involving the Hong Kong garrison since the handover, including the casualties and crew information. He also enquired the impact on the electricity supply by the crash and whether the garrison notified the authorities of the training in accordance with garrison law. MP James To said the crash may involve military confidential information and would not notify the government until the site was cleared. To added however that public safety could be harmed by bullets or wrecks if it was not announced immediately. Jeremy Tam, a former pilot and now a pro-democracy legislator, agreed the delay on announcement and cordoning off the area could worry hikers who had no knowledge on the event. He said Civil Aviation Department has no power to investigate and the crash would be dealt with by the garrison.\n\nJournalists searched for the wreck near Tsing Tam reservoir. On 2 April, a 25 square metres of flatted bushes with cracked trunk and cable was found on a slope near Kap Lung Forest Trail. Fuel could also be smelled from the area. Debris of the helicopter including suspected control panel, buttons of equipment were seen alongside pieces of military uniform, glucose injections, and flying manual of Harbin Z-9. However, no large pieces of wrecks or blood stain were seen. Lunchboxes and water bottles of Chinese brand Nongfu Spring were disposed on a nearby path that appears to be created recently. Response: [RequestOutput(request_id=19, prompt='<bos><start_of_turn>user\nPrevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# 2020 Hong Kong Garrison helicopter crash\n\nA military helicopter of Hong Kong Garrison of Chinese People\'s Liberation Army crashed in Tai Lam Country Park, Hong Kong on 30 March 2020 during a flight training operation, reportedly killing four. The news was only confirmed a day later but no information was released regarding the crew. This is the first recorded aircraft accident involving the Chinese troops in Hong Kong since handover, and raised speculation on the details.\n\n## Accident\n\nAccording to the government, which received notification from the garrison, the helicopter was conducting flight training operation in the area of the Tai Lam Country Park in that afternoon. Villagers in Chuen Lung who witnessed the crash said there were heavy fog when the helicopter is believed to have crashed into an electricity transmission tower by accident. The chopper\'s noise stopped after explosions were heard, but no smoke or fire could be seen. The lost helicopter is believed to be a Harbin Z-9 (no. 6202).\n\nCLP Group confirmed a voltage dip incident at 4:48\xa0p.m. at a 400kV overhead line power cable connecting Lung Kwu Tan and Sha Tin which lasted for less than 0.1 seconds. The fire service received 42 reports of lift malfunction across the city within 15 minutes after the incident, while Chuen Lung residents also reported a sudden loss of electricity. Photos showed the tower and parts of the cable were damaged.\n\nA dozen of military vehicles and large group of soldiers were spotted by nearby Lui Kung Tin villagers soon after the accident. A number of helicopter flew near the location but turned away likely because of the weather condition. According to the villagers and hikers, at 7 a.m. on the next day more than a hundred military personnel, along with many police officers, entered Tai Lam Country Park via Lui Kung Tin. Some had shovels and other tools in their hands. By 9 a.m. the site was sealed off by the police and the garrison. Witnesses said a senior soldier from Hong Kong Garrison claimed there was a military exercise for the large presence of soldiers. The officers stayed for hours and remained at the crash site after 2 p.m., while CLP maintenance vehicles also travelled uphill afterwards.\n\n## Reaction\n\nThe government confirmed the news after 8 p.m. through press release, more than 27 hours after the accident. The Chinese statement described it as a crash but the English version termed "accident". Neither provided details about what had happened apart from no ground injuries.... A notification was received from the Chinese People\'s Liberation Army Hong Kong Garrison (the Garrison) today to inform the Security Bureau of an accident involving a helicopter of the Garrison which occurred in the afternoon of March 30 during the Garrison\'s flight training operation conducted in the area of the Tai Lam Country Park. The incident did not involve any injury to people or damage to residences. The Garrison is handling and investigating the incident in accordance with the Garrison Law. The Security Bureau will continue to liaise with the Garrison on the incident.The fire service said they have no relevant record on handling a helicopter incident in Tai Lam.\n\nThe pro-democracy camp urged for transparency in this event. Eddie Chu, who was one of the first public figures to break the news, demanded the Security Bureau to reveal more details on the most serious accident involving the Hong Kong garrison since the handover, including the casualties and crew information. He also enquired the impact on the electricity supply by the crash and whether the garrison notified the authorities of the training in accordance with garrison law. MP James To said the crash may involve military confidential information and would not notify the government until the site was cleared. To added however that public safety could be harmed by bullets or wrecks if it was not announced immediately. Jeremy Tam, a former pilot and now a pro-democracy legislator, agreed the delay on announcement and cordoning off the area could worry hikers who had no knowledge on the event. He said Civil Aviation Department has no power to investigate and the crash would be dealt with by the garrison.\n\nJournalists searched for the wreck near Tsing Tam reservoir. On 2 April, a 25 square metres of flatted bushes with cracked trunk and cable was found on a slope near Kap Lung Forest Trail. Fuel could also be smelled from the area. Debris of the helicopter including suspected control panel, buttons of equipment were seen alongside pieces of military uniform, glucose injections, and flying manual of Harbin Z-9. However, no large pieces of wrecks or blood stain were seen. Lunchboxes and water bottles of Chinese brand Nongfu Spring were disposed on a nearby path that appears to be created recently. A day later, a group of men was seen carrying a suspected plane debris away. None told the journalists of their identity or the item they took away.\n\n## References\n\nMarch 2020\nPeople\'s Liberation Army Hong Kong garrison\n2020 in Hong Kong\nAccidents and incidents Translation: # 2013 European Junior Badminton Championships ‚Äì Boys' singles

The Boys' singles tournament of the 2013 European Junior Badminton Championships was held from April 23 to 28. The defending champion was Zulfadli Zulkiffli from Malaysia.

## Seeded

 Rasmus Gemal Kehlet (quarter-finals)
 Lucas Claerbout (semi-finals)
 Emil Holst (third round)
 Toma Junior Popov (final)
 Kalle Koljonen (third round)
 Luka Mihaljevic (quarter-finals)
 Milan Dratva (quarter-finals)
 Daniel Lundgaard (third round)

## External links

* Tournament draw

2013 European Junior Badminton Championships
European Junior Badminton Championships
2013 in youth sport
Junior
[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Angelo Azzi\n\nAngelo Azzi is an Italian and Swiss biochemist, author and academic serving as a Professor Emeritus in the Institute of Biochemistry and Molecular Medicine at the University of Bern and Adjunct Faculty Member at Tufts University.\n\nAzzi\'s work focuses on the biochemistry of enzymes, gene regulation, and metabolism, with an emphasis on vitamin E (alpha-tocopherol), antioxidants, and signaling pathways involving protein kinase C and diacylglycerol kinase. He has received awards, including the 2002 Vitamin Prize from the Society for Applied Vitamin Research, the Society of Free Radicals\' Lifetime Achievement Award in 2014, the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology Distinguished Service Award in 2016, and the Nencki Award from the Nencki Institute of Experimental Biology in 2016.\n\nAzzi is a Foreign Member of the Polish Academy of Sciences and a Lifetime Honorary Member of the Oxygen Club of California. He also holds editorial roles, including Editor-in-Chief of journals such as Molecular Aspects of Medicine and Aspects of Molecular Medicine.\n\n## Education and career\n\nAzzi earned an MD in 1963 from the University of Padua, followed by a PhD in General Pathology in 1969 and a PhD in Biochemistry in 1970. He worked at Institute of General Pathology under Massimo Aloisi, where he explored mitochondrial function and later collaborated with Giovanni Felice Azzone, contributing to the discovery of the permeability transition pore. In 1966, he pursued postdoctoral research as a Fellow in the Department of Biochemistry at the University of Bristol, focusing on mitochondrial transporters, and continued as a Research Fellow in the Department of Biophysics at the University of Pennsylvania from 1967 to 1969, studying mitochondrial membrane functions. Returning to Italy in the early 1970s, he became a Professor in 1973. In 1977, he relocated to Bern, Switzerland, becoming a Professor of Biochemistry at the University of Bern.\n\nAt the University of Bern, Azzi was the Head of the Department of the Medical Chemistry Institute, later serving as Professor and Director of the Institute of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology from 1984 to 2005, when he was named Professor Emeritus.\n\nAzzi served on the Advisory Board of UNESCO\'s International Scientific Advisory Board/International Biological and Scientific Programme (ISAB/IBSP) from 1997 to 2015. During this period, he held the position of President of the International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology (IUBMB) from 2006 to 2012 and Past-President from 2013 to 2015. His leadership also extended to the Society for Free Radical Research International, where he acted as President from 2007 to 2010 and Past-President from 2010 to 2013.\n\n## Research\n\nAzzi has researched the mechanisms through which vitamin E and lycopene prevent prostate cancer and has discovered the transport carrier for aspartic and glutamic acids in mitochondria. He has evaluated vitamin E\'s roles beyond its antioxidative properties, highlighting its involvement in cellular signaling, gene regulation, and disease prevention. In a joint study with Achim Stocker, he explored the functions of Œ±-tocopherol, revealing its selective antioxidant role, non-antioxidant mechanisms, and effects on cellular processes, including protein kinase C inhibition and gene transcription. He also investigated the effects of Œ±-tocopherol on cell proliferation, demonstrating its concentration-dependent inhibition of vascular smooth muscle cell proliferation through protein kinase C inhibition. His findings suggested that Œ±-tocopherol has non-antioxidant molecular functions, acting as a ligand for proteins that regulate signal transduction and gene expression, with no compensatory antioxidant response observed in its deficiency. Building upon this, he looked into the effect of lycopene, alone or with other antioxidants, on the growth of prostate carcinoma cell lines, and found that lycopene alone was not a potent inhibitor, but its combination with Œ±-tocopherol strongly inhibited cell proliferation in a synergistic manner. Furthermore, examining the role of protein kinase C in signal transduction, he emphasized its activation by various agents and involvement in tumor promotion, while calling for additional research into its physiological substrates. His work also analyzed the formation of hydrogen peroxide in the mitochondrial respiratory chain, identifying the superoxide radical as a precursor of HO generation.\n\nAzzi has published course books, including Membrane Proteins: Isolation and Characterization (1986), Dynamics of Membrane Proteins and Cellular Energetics (1988), and Organelles in Eukaryotic Cells: Molecular Structure and Interactions (1989). In 1989, he co-edited Molecular Basis of Membrane-Associated Diseases with Zdenek Drahota and Sergio Papa, examining molecular changes in biological membranes linked to diseases like lysosomal, peroxisomal, and mitochondrial disorders, enzyme defects, and receptor abnormalities related to oncogenes. That same year, he co-edited Anion Carriers of Mitochondrial Membranes with Katarzyna A. Nalecz, Maciej J. Nalecz, and Lech Wojtczak, covering the structure, function, isolation, transport kinetics, and metabolic regulation of mitochondrial anion carriers. In 2000, he co-authored Antioxidants in Diabetes Management (Oxidative Stress and Disease) with Peter Rosen, Hans J. Tritschler, and Glenn A. King, exploring oxidative stress in diabetes and the potential of antioxidant therapies. Reviewing the book for Trends in Endocrinology and Metabolism, Kailash Prasad wrote, "the authors should be commended for an admirable job in framing a succinct review of the pathophysiology associated with the development of diabetes and its associated complications, and opportunities that antioxidants might offer for therapy in diabetes."\n\n## Awards and honors\n \n\n* 1994 ‚Äì Foreign Member, Polish Academy of Sciences\n\n* 2001 ‚Äì Lifetime Honorary Member, Oxygen Club of California\n\n* 2002 ‚Äì Vitamin Prize, Society for Applied Vitamin Research\n\n* 2014 ‚Äì Lifetime Achievement Award, Society of Free Radicals Europe\n\n* 2016 ‚Äì Distinguished Service Award, International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology\n\n* 2016 ‚Äì Nencki Award, Nencki Institute of Experimental Biology\n\n## Selected books\n\n* Membrane Proteins: Isolation and Characterization (1986) ISBN 978-3540170143\n\n* Molecular Basis of Membrane-Associated Diseases (1989) ISBN 978-3642744174\n\n* Organelles in Eukaryotic Cells: Molecular Structure and Interactions (1989) ISBN 978-0306433887\n\n* Anion Carriers of Mitochondrial Membranes (1989) ISBN 978-3642745416\n\n* Antioxidants in Diabetes Management (Oxidative Stress and Disease) (2000) ISBN 978-0824788445\n\n## Selected articles\n\n* Loschen, G., Azzi, A., Richter, C., & Floh√©, L. (1974). Superoxide radicals as precursors of mitochondrial hydrogen peroxide. FEBS letters, 42(1), 68-72.\n\n* Boscoboinik, D., Szewczyk, A., Hensey, C., & Azzi, A. (1991). Inhibition of cell proliferation by alpha-tocopherol. Role of protein kinase C. Journal of Biological Chemistry, 266(10), 6188-6194.\n\n* Azzi, A., & Stocker, A. (2000). Vitamin E: non-antioxidant roles. Progress in lipid Research, 39(3), 231-255.\n\n* Brigelius-Floh√©, R., Kelly, F. J., Salonen, J. T., Neuzil, J., Zingg, J. M., & Azzi, A. (2002). The European perspective on vitamin E: current knowledge and future research. The American journal of clinical nutrition, 76(4), 703-716.\n\n* Azzi, A. (2007). Molecular mechanism of Œ±-tocopherol action. Free Radical Biology and Medicine, 43(1), 16-21.\n\n* Azzi, A. (2024). Oxidative Stress: Cannot be Measured, Localized, Prevented, or Treated. Medical Research Archives, 12(2).\n\n## References\n\nBiochemists\n21st-century science writers\nMembers of the Polish Academy of Sciences\nAcademic staff of the University of Bern\nTufts University faculty\nUniversity of Padua alumni', 'role': 'user'}]

235279, 2648, 617, 2895, 21143, 108, 15957, 576, 165128, 54088, 107, 108, 106, 2516, 108, 1], encoder_prompt=None, encoder_prompt_token_ids=None, prompt_logprobs=None, outputs=[CompletionOutput(index=0, text="# # Problem of the day\n\nIn mathematics education, a problem of the day (POD) is a short mathematical problem or puzzle presented to students at the beginning of a class session. The purpose of a problem of the day is to engage students in mathematical thinking, to provide a mental warm-up, and to encourage students to think creatively and critically about mathematics. Problem of the day activities can be used in any mathematics class, from elementary school to university level.\n\n## History\n\nThe concept of a problem of the day has been used in mathematics education for many years, particularly in the context of the Problem of the Day Club in the United Kingdom. The Problem of the Day Club was founded in 1983 by John Steiner, a mathematics teacher at Sevenoaks School in Kent. The club was designed to promote mathematical thinking and problem-solving skills among students.\n\n## Format and usage\n\nA problem of the day is typically presented at the beginning of a mathematics class session, often on the chalkboard or through a digital platform. The problem is designed to be accessible to all students in the class, regardless of their current level of mathematical knowledge. Students are encouraged to work on the problem individually or in small groups, and to share their solutions and reasoning with the class at the end of the period.\n\n## Benefits\n\nThere are several benefits to using a problem of the day in mathematics education:\n\nEncourages critical thinking: By presenting students with problems that require them to think creatively and critically, a problem of the day helps to develop their problem-solving skills.\nBuilds confidence: When students are able to solve a problem of the day, it can boost their confidence in their mathematical abilities.\nImproves communication skills: Working on a problem of the day in a group setting helps students to develop their communication skills as they discuss their ideas and solutions with each other.\nIncreases engagement: Presenting a problem of the day at the beginning of a class session can help to increase student engagement and make the class more interesting.\n\n## Sample problems\n\nSample problems of the day can include a variety of mathematical topics, from basic arithmetic to more advanced concepts like calculus or geometry. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. Magic Squares: Can you create a 3x3 magic square where the sum of each row, column, and diagonal is 15?\n2. Number Patterns: What is the next number in the sequence 1, 2, 4, 7, 11, 16?\n3. Area of a Triangle: If the sides of a triangle are 3, 4, and 5, what is the area of the triangle?\n4. The Josephus Problem: 10 people are standing in a circle. Starting with the first person, every second person is eliminated until only one person remains. Who is the last person standing?\n5. The Birthday Paradox: What is the probability that at least two people in a room of 23 people share the same birthday?\n\n## Variations\n\nThere are many variations of the problem of the day concept that can be used in mathematics education. Some examples include:\n\nMath Minute: A shorter, more concise version of the problem of the day, typically lasting only a few minutes.\nPuzzle of the Day: A more open-ended problem that requires students to think creatively and come up with multiple solutions.\nBrain Teaser of the Day: A short, humorous or quirky problem that is designed to make students laugh while also engaging their mathematical thinking.\nChallenge of the Week: A more complex problem that students can work on throughout the week and present their solutions on Friday.\n\n## Resources\n\nThere are many resources available to help teachers create and implement a problem of the day in their mathematics classes. Some examples include:\n\nMathematical Association of America: The Mathematical Association of America (MAA) offers a variety of problem solving resources, including a Problem of the Day section on their website.\nNational Council of Teachers of Mathematics: The National Council of Teachers of Mathematics (NCTM) also offers problem solving resources, including a Problem of the Day section on their website.\nOnline Resources: There are many online resources available, such as MathOverflow, Math Stack Exchange, and various educational websites that offer problem of the day puzzles.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nA problem of the day is a powerful tool for engaging students in mathematical thinking and problem-solving. By presenting students with interesting and challenging problems, teachers can help to develop their critical thinking skills, build their confidence, and increase their engagement in mathematics. With the many resources available, there is no shortage of problems to choose from, and the possibilities for variation are endless.\n\n## References\n\n1. Steiner, J. (1983). Translation: # # Problem of the day

In mathematics education, a problem of the day (POD) is a short mathematical problem or puzzle presented to students at the beginning of a class session. The purpose of a problem of the day is to engage students in mathematical thinking, to provide a mental warm-up, and to encourage students to think creatively and critically about mathematics. Problem of the day activities can be used in any mathematics class, from elementary school to university level.

## History

The concept of a problem of the day has been used in mathematics education for many years, particularly in the context of the Problem of the Day Club in the United Kingdom. The Problem of the Day Club was founded in 1983 by John Steiner, a mathematics teacher at Sevenoaks School in Kent. The club was designed to promote mathematical thinking and problem-solving skills among students.

## Format and usage

A problem of the day is typically presented at the beginning of a mathematics class session, often on the chalkboard or through a digital platform. The problem is designed to be accessible to all students in the class, regardless of their current level of mathematical knowledge. Students are encouraged to work on the problem individually or in small groups, and to share their solutions and reasoning with the class at the end of the period.

## Benefits

There are several benefits to using a problem of the day in mathematics education:

Encourages critical thinking: By presenting students with problems that require them to think creatively and critically, a problem of the day helps to develop their problem-solving skills.
Builds confidence: When students are able to solve a problem of the day, it can boost their confidence in their mathematical abilities.
Improves communication skills: Working on a problem of the day in a group setting helps students to develop their communication skills as they discuss their ideas and solutions with each other.
Increases engagement: Presenting a problem of the day at the beginning of a class session can help to increase student engagement and make the class more interesting.

## Sample problems

Sample problems of the day can include a variety of mathematical topics, from basic arithmetic to more advanced concepts like calculus or geometry. Here are a few examples:

1. Magic Squares: Can you create a 3x3 magic square where the sum of each row, column, and diagonal is 15?
2. Number Patterns: What is the next number in the sequence 1, 2, 4, 7, 11, 16?
3. Area of a Triangle: If the sides of a triangle are 3, 4, and 5, what is the area of the triangle?
4. The Josephus Problem: 10 people are standing in a circle. Starting with the first person, every second person is eliminated until only one person remains. Who is the last person standing?
5. The Birthday Paradox: What is the probability that at least two people in a room of 23 people share the same birthday?

## Variations

There are many variations of the problem of the day concept that can be used in mathematics education. Some examples include:

Math Minute: A shorter, more concise version of the problem of the day, typically lasting only a few minutes.
Puzzle of the Day: A more open-ended problem that requires students to think creatively and come up with multiple solutions.
Brain Teaser of the Day: A short, humorous or quirky problem that is designed to make students laugh while also engaging their mathematical thinking.
Challenge of the Week: A more complex problem that students can work on throughout the week and present their solutions on Friday.

## Resources

There are many resources available to help teachers create and implement a problem of the day in their mathematics classes. Some examples include:

Mathematical Association of America: The Mathematical Association of America (MAA) offers a variety of problem solving resources, including a Problem of the Day section on their website.
National Council of Teachers of Mathematics: The National Council of Teachers of Mathematics (NCTM) also offers problem solving resources, including a Problem of the Day section on their website.
Online Resources: There are many online resources available, such as MathOverflow, Math Stack Exchange, and various educational websites that offer problem of the day puzzles.

## Conclusion

A problem of the day is a powerful tool for engaging students in mathematical thinking and problem-solving. By presenting students with interesting and challenging problems, teachers can help to develop their critical thinking skills, build their confidence, and increase their engagement in mathematics. With the many resources available, there is no shortage of problems to choose from, and the possibilities for variation are endless.

Translation: # The Blackwater Lightship

The Blackwater Lightship is a 1992 novel by Irish author Colm T√≥ib√≠n. It is a fictionalized account of the Irish poet Thomas MacGreevy's life.

## Plot

The novel is set in the time period between 1939 and 1945, during World War II. It takes place in a variety of locations including Ireland, England, and France. The main character, Helena, is a young woman from a wealthy family who is engaged to a man she does not love. She meets and falls in love with a poet named MacGreevy, who is living in a lighthouse in County Wexford. The two have a passionate affair, but Helena eventually breaks it off in order to marry her fianc√©. MacGreevy goes on to become a successful poet, while Helena's life takes a more tragic turn.

## Reception

The Blackwater Lightship received generally positive reviews from critics. It was praised for its lyrical prose and its exploration of complex themes such as love, war, and art. However, some critics felt that the novel was too slow-paced and that the characters were not fully developed.

## Awards and nominations

The Blackwater Lightship was shortlisted for the Booker Prize in 1992. It also won the Guardian Fiction Prize.

## Themes

The novel explores a variety of themes, including love, war, art, and the passage of time. It also touches on the impact of history on individuals and the way in which people are shaped by their pasts.

## Critical reception

The Blackwater Lightship was generally well-received by critics. It was praised for its lyrical prose and its exploration of complex themes. However, some critics felt that the novel was too slow-paced and that the characters were not fully developed.

## Legacy

The Blackwater Lightship is considered to be one of Colm T√≥ib√≠n's most important works. It has been widely read and studied, and it has helped to establish T√≥ib√≠n as one of the leading writers of his generation.

During the mid-1980s, Gusev was a lieutenant general serving as deputy commander of the Carpathian Military District. \n\nGusev was subsequently appointed as head of the Soviet military mission in Angola in 1987, succeeding Lieutenant General Leonid Kuzmenko. In this role, Gusev directly planned and supervised combat operations for the People's Armed Forces of Liberation of Angola (FAPLA), with the oversight of Angolan Defence Minister Pedro Pedal√©. He was the senior Soviet general officer involved in the Battle of Cuito Cuanavale. Throughout the battle, Gusev personally briefed Angolan president Jos√© Eduardo dos Santos on the military situation.\n\nGusev was a controversial figure among the Soviet military forces in Angola. He often vetoed commendations for Soviet enlisted personnel and junior officers who had been directly engaged in hostilities. The Soviet troops primarily served in technical and support roles, although circumstances often dictated they fight alongside their Angolan peers if attacked by UNITA insurgents or South African expeditionary forces. Gusev also garnered criticism for ordering offensives without taking into account the logistical challenges and technical shortcomings of the Angolan forces expected to execute these complex operations. \n\nGusev published his memoirs after his retirement from military service.\n\n## References\n\n1932 births\n2024 deaths\nSoviet lieutenant generals\nSoviet military personnel of the Angolan Civil War\nPeople of the South African Border War\nPeople from Udmurtia", 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # The Legend of the White Horse

The Legend of the White Horse is an album released by American jazz trumpeter and composer Wadada Leo Smith and his band, the Golden Quartet, on the Silkheart label in 1997. It features performances by Smith, bassist Sirone, drummer Pheeroan akLaff, and percussionist Kahil El'Zabar.

## Reception

In his review for AllMusic, Alex Henderson states "Smith's music on The Legend of the White Horse is a combination of free jazz, avant-garde jazz, and spiritual jazz. ... The music is accessible despite its avant-garde leanings, and The Legend of the White Horse is a fine place to start for those who are new to the trumpeter."

The Penguin Guide to Jazz notes that "the music is disciplined and controlled, as always with Smith, but there is a relaxation to the pace that the earlier albums lack."

## Track listing

All compositions by Wadada Leo Smith
 "The Legend of the White Horse" - 10:26 
 "Mysteries of the Universe" - 10:02 
 "The Seventh Portal" - 3:55 
 "The Light of the Universe" - 3:28 
 "The Creation of the Universe" - 8:53 
 "The Universe" - 7:29 
 "The Beginning of the Universe" - 5:59

## Personnel

* Wadada Leo Smith - trumpet, flugelhorn, percussion

* Sirone - bass

* Pheeroan akLaff - drums

* Kahil El'Zabar - percussion, drums, bells, chimes, chimes of freedom, kalimba, voice, vocalizations

Translation: # 2017‚Äì18 Washington State Cougars men's basketball team

The 2017‚Äì18 Washington State Cougars men's basketball team represented Washington State University during the 2017‚Äì18 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The Cougars, led by second-year head coach Ernie Kent, played their home games at the Beasley Coliseum in Pullman, Washington as members of the Pac-12 Conference. They finished the season 13‚Äì19, 6‚Äì12 in Pac-12 play to finish in a tie for ninth place. They defeated Oregon State in the first round of the Pac-12 tournament before losing in the quarterfinals to Arizona.

## Previous season

The Cougars finished the 2016‚Äì17 season 9‚Äì22, 4‚Äì14 in Pac-12 play to finish in a tie for 10th place. They lost in the first round of the Pac-12 tournament to California.

## Preseason

The Cougars were picked to finish in 10th place in the Pac-12 preseason media poll. Robert Franks was named to the preseason All-Pac-12 team.

Translation: # Kalmyks campaign against Kazakhs (1627)

Kalmyks campaign against Kazakhs (1627) ‚Äî Chokhur-taishi's campaign against the Kazakhs.

In the early years of Yesim Khan's reign, the threat of Kalmyk incursions into Kazakh lands persisted. According to the Book of the Great Map, in 1627, some Kalmyk tribes neighbored the Kazakhs in the areas around the Sarysu and Kenderlik rivers. In the fall of the same year, the Kalmyk leader Chokhur-Taisha, who had previously been defeated by the Kazakhs, launched a new campaign against the Kazakh Khanate. He managed to assemble an army of about 40,000 men.

The results of this campaign were reported by Russian musketeers who had returned from Turkmen captivity: "This autumn, a force of forty thousand Kalmyks marched on the Kazakh Horde, and the Kazakh king, with his people, defeated and dispersed them. The remnants of the Kalmyk army, numbering about two thousand men, retreated to the upper reaches of the Emba River." This indicates that the Kazakh army delivered a crushing defeat to Chokhur-Taisha's forces.

As Yesim Khan's authority strengthened, there were notable successes in the struggle against the Kalmyks. The Kazakhs managed to drive the Kalmyk tribes, who had been roaming the valleys of the Irtysh River, to its right bank. I. Y. Zlatkin noted: "Lake Yamyshevo, which two or three decades earlier had been one of the centers of Oirat migrations, had now become their frontier point."

## Reference

History of Kalmykia
Battles involving the Kazakh Khanate
Military history of Kazakhstan
Kazakh Khanate

[{'content': "Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Tyers Lightning SC\n\nTyers Soccer Club is a soccer club based in Tyers, Victoria, Australia. The club was originally founded in 1982 and currently competes in Latrobe Valley Soccer League and are often to referred to as the Tyers Lightning.\n\nThe club was formed in order to bring high level competitive football to the town of Tyers, drawing its players and fans from nearby, larger towns including Yallourn North, Glengarry and from Latrobe City's biggest city, Traralgon, which is less than 10 kilometres away.\n\nThe club is still yet to win a senior men's LVSL title but did win back-to-back women's league titles in 2014 and 2015, as well as a hattrick of grand final victories in 2014, 2015 and 2016.\n\n## Club forms and accepted into LVSL (1982-2008)\n\nTyers' journey into the Latrobe Valley Soccer League was somewhat unexpected, for the township holds less than 1000 people, making it one of Victoria's smallest towns to have a soccer clubs competing in an organised league.\n\nHowever, the proximity of the club to other major towns - more than 30,000 people live within 10 minutes' drive - has always ensured the club's viability and popularity.\n\nThe club's journey started modestly with junior teams in the Under-8 and Under-10 categories, playing on the school football oval. In 1984, the Tyers Recreation Reserve designated land for a soccer pitch, which is where the club plays today. Early efforts to create a functional soccer environment included mowing the pitch with lawn mowers, selling food from car boots, and repurposing a disused turbine box from the Loy Yang Power Station as change rooms. The goals themselves were handmade by the founding families. \n\nA significant development came in 1986 with the construction of the original pavilion, funded by a major grant from the Latrobe City Council. The pavilion included a canteen, toilets, and an changing room. \n\nBy 1992, the club had expanded to include an Under-12 team, with subsequent progress to full junior teams as the children grew. In 1996, the club entered its first senior team in the LVSL.\n\n## Women's team emerges as a local force (2009-)\n\nWhilst Tyers' men's team continued to struggle on the field, the formation of a women's league in 2009 signalled something of a turning point for the club's fortunes.\n\nTyers' women's team finished fourth in the LVSL in 2010 but rose above all comers in the finals series, winning the grand final to claim the very first of silverware for the club. \n\nAfter finishing runner's up in the 2012 Browne-Huizer Cup, the women's team finished runner's up in the league in 2013, signalling their arrival as a championship threat. \n\nTyers then broke through in major style in 2014, winning the LSVL's women's league, the league grand final and the Browne-Huizer Cup - the first pieces of silverware the club had claimed at senior level in men's or women's football. \n\nThey followed it up in 2015 with another victory in the league and the grand final, but fell short in the league in 2016, finishing as runner's up. \n\nThe club celebrated its 40-year anniversary in 2022.\n\n## Club colors and badge\n\nThe club plays in gold and green jerseys.\n\n## Stadium\n\nThe club plays its home matches at Bailie Reserve (also known as Tyers Recreation Reserve), which has a capacity of 500 (with a seating capacity of 100).\n\nIn 2011, the club enhanced its facilities with the installation of two major lighting towers, made possible through a grant. Two years later, in 2013, another grant facilitated the construction of a new pavilion alongside the original structure, featuring updated home-and-away change rooms and a dedicated referee room.\n\n## Club achievements\n\n* Latrobe Valley Soccer League Women's\nChampions (2): 2014, 2015\nRunner's Up (2): 2013, 2016\nGrand Finals Winners (4): 2010, 2014, 2015, 2016\n\n* LVSL Women's Browne-Huizer Cup\nChampions (1): 2014\nRunner's Up (1): 2012\n\n## External links\n\n* Tyers Lightning Soccer Club\n\nAssociation football clubs established in 1982\n1982 establishments in Australia\nSoccer clubs in Victoria (state)", 'role': 'user'}]

film directed by Maurice Tourneur and starring Wallace Beery, Noah Beery, and Anna Q. Nilsson. Based on the 1826 novel of the same name by James Fenimore Cooper, the film was produced by Famous Players‚ÄìLasky and distributed by Paramount Pictures. It is not known whether the film currently survives.\n\n## Plot\n\nIn 1757, during the French and Indian War, two British officers, Major Duncan Heyward and Lieutenant Magua, are ambushed by Indians. Translation: # The Last of the Mohicans (1920 film)

The Last of the Mohicans is a 1920 American silent adventure film directed by Maurice Tourneur and starring Wallace Beery, Noah Beery, and Anna Q. Nilsson. Based on the 1826 novel of the same name by James Fenimore Cooper, the film was produced by Famous Players‚ÄìLasky and distributed by Paramount Pictures. It is not known whether the film currently survives.

## Plot

In 1757, during the French and Indian War, two British officers, Major Duncan Heyward and Lieutenant Magua, are ambushed by Indians. Heyward is saved by Chingachgook, the last of the Mohicans, and his son Uncas. Chingachgook adopts Heyward as his son. The three men travel to a British fort.

Heyward falls in love with Cora Munro, the daughter of the fort's commander. Cora's sister Alice is in love with Magua. Magua is a Huron chief, and is plotting to kidnap and marry Alice.

The British soldiers must go to war. Chingachgook, Uncas, and Heyward stay behind to protect the women. Magua and his men attack the fort, and the three men fight to save the women.

## Cast

* Wallace Beery as Chingachgook

* Noah Beery as Magua

* Anna Q. Nilsson as Cora Munro

* Edythe Chapman as Alice Munro

* Wallace MacDonald as Major Duncan Heyward

* Lloyd Whitlock as Uncas

* George Periolat as Huron Chief

* William H. Tooker as Colonel Munro

* Robert Cain as Captain

## Production

The Last of the Mohicans was the second film adaptation of James Fenimore Cooper's novel. It was directed by Maurice Tourneur, who had made his American debut with the highly successful adventure film The Last of the Knickerbockers (1919). It was filmed on location in the Adirondack Mountains of New York State.

## Reception

The Last of the Mohicans was well received by the critics. A review in The New York Times praised the film, stating, "The story has been told with a faithfulness to the original that is remarkable and yet with so much of the spirit of the book that the screen version has the same thrilling and absorbing qualities as the book itself." The reviewer added, "The Last of the Mohicans, as presented by the Famous Players‚ÄìLasky organization, is a production that will live in the memory of those who see it."

## Preservation status

The Last of the Mohicans is now considered a lost film, although a few still photographs survive.

## In popular culture

The novel and its film adaptations have been parodied in the fourth season of the TV series The Good Place. In the episode "The Answer", the residents of The Good Place are assigned to a series of "bad place" tasks based on famous works of literature, and the group's task is to re-enact The Last of the Mohicans. The episode includes many of the film's plot points, including a tomahawk fight between Jason and Derek, and Eleanor and Janet playing the sisters Alice and Cora.

Translation: # The Voice of the People (Philippines)

The Voice of the People (abbreviated as TVOP) is a Philippine television public affairs show broadcast by GMA Network. Hosted by Jessica Soho, it premiered on October 24, 2021, replacing State of the Nation with Jessica Soho.

## Overview

The Voice of the People is a public affairs program hosted by Jessica Soho which aims to discuss the most pressing issues in the country. The program is a continuation of State of the Nation with Jessica Soho, which ran from 2016 to 2021.

## Hosts

* Jessica Soho (2021‚Äìpresent)

## Production

The Voice of the People is produced by GMA Public Affairs. The program was announced by GMA Network on August 19, 2021. The show is a continuation of State of the Nation with Jessica Soho, which Soho hosted from 2016 to 2021.

## Ratings

According to AGB Nielsen Philippines' Nationwide Urban Television Audience Measurement People in Television Homes, the pilot episode of The Voice of the People earned a 10.2% rating. While the episode broadcast on March 26, 2022, earned a 10.7% rating.

## External links

*

[{'content': 'Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Platon Rozhdestvensky\n\nPlaton (Rozhdestvensky) (; - April 20, 1934), born Porphyry Theodorovich Rozhdestvensky (), was the Russian Orthodox Archbishop of the Aleutians and North America from 1907 to 1914 and again from 1922 to 1934.\n\n## Early life\n\nPlaton was born as Porphyry Theodorovich Rozhdestvensky on February 23, 1866, to a priest near Kursk, Russia. In 1886 he graduated from Kursk Seminary and in 1894 he enrolled in the Kiev Theological Academy where he took on the name Platon and graduated the following year, obtaining a Master of Theology in the same institution in 1898. After graduation he continued to work at the university as professor, rector, and eventually dean.\n\n## Bishop\n\nOn June 3, 1902, he was consecrated as Bishop of Kiev. He was elected to the Second State Duma on February 12, 1907, due to his popularity amongst the locals in Kiev.\n\n## Arrival in America\n\nPlaton was elected as Archbishop of North America for the first time on June 8, 1907, where he would preside for the next seven years. He faced many challenges including a priest shortage, ethnic nationalism amongst the diaspora populations, and unpopularity of the church (in part due to resistance towards Russian hegemony). Platon\'s primary concern was the question of administering Ukrainian and Russian churches, and most ethnic missions were largely overlooked. In December 1908, he also founded the Russian Orthodox Christian Immigrant Society of North America, with the goal of protecting newly arrived immigrants from Austria-Hungary, Galicia, and Russia.\n\nUnder Platon\'s leadership, efforts were made to nationalize the church. In February 1908, Platon organized an Albanian Orthodox Mission in America that included six parishes in Hudson, Massachusetts in response to a petition made by the local Albanian population after an independently owned Greek church refused to bury an Albanian nationalist. In 1909, a bill was vetoed by Governor Charles E. Hughes in the New York State Legislature after protests by the local Greek population. The law would have effectively placed the Greek parishes under Russian control. In a letter to Dean Pashkovsky discussing the possibility of a more unified church in North America, Platon expressed frustration with the Greek led opposition, stating "...it seems it [a unified leadership] is unfeasible when taking into consideration the self sufficiency of the Greeks...in all matters religion and faith". In 1913, a group of 19 Serbian churches briefly seceded until reconciliation was made in which the Russian delegation agreed to be more solicitous of Serbian complaints.\n\nIn 1912, he moved the first seminary in North America, St. Tikhon\'s, from Minneapolis, Minnesota to Tenafly, New Jersey in order to be closer to church administration, and was renamed St. Platon\'s Seminary. It was closed down in 1923 due to financial difficulties.\n\n## Return to Russia\n\nUpon his return to Russia, Platon was appointed Archbishop of Kishinev and Khotyn on March 20, 1914, before being transferred to the see of Kartalin and Kakheti on December 5, 1915. Platon remained there until the restoration of autocephaly of the Georgian Orthodox Church in 1917, after of which he served as bishop of Kherson and Odessa until having to flee due to the Russian Revolution. Platon was a major participant in the All-Russian Council, and was considered as a candidate for Patriarchate of the Russian Church. During the council, Platon also suggested appointing a Greek bishop "who has studied in a Russian theological institute" in North America. During the council, Platon was also given the task of negotiating with the Bolsheviks during the Russian Revolution. On December that year he was elected to the Holy Synod and represented a delegation in Kiev in January 1918 in order to address the movement for autocephaly in Ukraine.\n\n## John Dudikoff\n\nPlaton first met Father John Dudikoff sometime in 1913, over a disagreement over finances. Dudikoff followed Platon to Russia in which he accused, in his expose, of various scandals of violence within the church, including adultery, homosexuality, orgies, embezzlement, prostitution and rape. Platon was also accused of being a close advisor and friend of German ally Pavlo Skoropadsky and of instigating a pogrom while in Ukraine. Both would come to sue each other in 1923 over these accusations.\n\n## Second tenure in America\n\nDue to the advances of the Bolsheviks in the Russian Civil War, Platon fled to America in 1919 as a refugee with his family. Facing resistance led by Father John Kedrovsky over the current bishop\'s alleged handling of church finances, Archbishop Alexander Nemolovsky in 1922 resigned and asked the Metropolitan to take over as the ruling hierarch of the diocese before leaving for Europe. On November 9 of that year he was confirmed in a sobor and established as the canonical Primate of North America; however this would be contested by Kedrovsky in later years. While serving as Archbishop of North America, Platon was pro forma retired by Patriarch Tikhon of Moscow in order to satisfy Bolshevik demands. Since Platon was already Metropolitan of Odessa, he kept this title during his second reign. Consequently, the Archdiocese of North America was elevated to Metropolia status and enjoyed a considerable amount of freedom from the Moscow Patriarchate. Metropolitan Platon inherited many new difficulties from his predecessor, such as a financial crisis and uncertainty of the future of the Moscow Patriarchate. By 1921, all funds from Russia to the North American diocese had been terminated.\n\nA second sobor was called on April 2, 1924, in Detroit, Michigan in which the North American diocese was declared "temporarily self-governing" due to difficulties in communication with the church in Russia. In later years, Platon would continue to rebuff affiliations with Russian Orthodox Church outside of Russia and the Moscow Patriarchate in order to maintain the diocese\'s independence. During his second tenure as hierarch, Platon was less amicable to movements to create a new, independent multi-ethnic church, and actively worked to undermine such efforts including any support for the newly established American Orthodox Catholic Church. Platon also faced many challenges to his own tenure; in 1925 Archbishop Adam Phillipovsky stormed Platon\'s residency with the assistance of a bomb squad from the Manhattan Police Department and physically threw the Archbishop out of the cathedral and onto the street. Phillipovsky would later be charged and arrested for contempt of court. Another threat to the diocese was Kedrovsky\'s schismatic "Living Church". Kedrovsky, who was suspended by Nemolovsky in 1918, claimed to be the true successor to the Russian Church in America by claiming he derived his authority from the Soviet Government, in contrast to Platon\'s staunch anti-Bolshevik stances. Kedrovsky would use this claim to sue over a hundred church properties. While mostly unsuccessful, he achieved a major victory in 1925 when the US courts recognized him as the legitimate owners of St Nicholas Russian Orthodox Cathedral in New York City.\n\n## Personal life and death\n\nPlaton was married in 1886. His wife gave birth to a daughter before dying in 1891; his daughter lived in Bulgaria with her family until the 1920s, where she eventually joined him in North America. On April 20, 1934, Platon died in New York, New York at the age of 68. He was buried at Saint Tikhon\'s Seminary. In 1946, Patriarch Alexy I posthumously lifted all ecclesiastical sanctions on him.\n\n## See also\n\n* List of primates of the Orthodox Church in America\n\n* 1917‚Äì18 Local Council of the Russian Orthodox Church\n\n* Renovationism\n\n* White √©migr√©\n\n## External links\n\n* Platon (Rozhdestvensky) of New York - OrthodoxWiki\n\n1866 births\n1934 deaths', 'role': 'user'}]

The presidential election was won by former President Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen of the National Liberation Party, who defeated Rafael √Ångel Calder√≥n Fournier of the Social Christian Unity Party and Ott√≥n Sol√≠s of the Citizens\' Action Party. Figueres\'s victory marked the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president\'s party had been re-elected.\n\n## Background\n\nThe 1990 elections were an important turning point in Costa Rican politics, marking the first time in 17 years that the ruling National Liberation Party (PLN) was not re-elected. Rafael √Ångel Calder√≥n Fournier, who was elected president, was the first member of the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC) to win the presidency. The victory of the PUSC, which had been founded in 1983, was a major upset, given the PLN\'s long history of dominance in Costa Rican politics. The election was also significant because it was the first time that a party not affiliated with the PLN or the National Unification Party (PUN) had won the presidency.\n\nThe PUSC\'s victory was attributed to several factors, including voter dissatisfaction with the PLN\'s handling of the economy, corruption scandals, and the party\'s support for a market-oriented economic policy. The election was also notable for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot.\n\nThe 1990s were a period of significant political and economic change in Costa Rica. The country experienced a period of economic growth and development, but it was also marked by challenges such as debt reduction, privatization, and the impact of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen\'s victory was the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president\'s party was re-elected, and it was a significant boost for the PLN, which had been facing challenges from the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC).\n\nThe election was also notable for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot. Translation: # 1996 Costa Rican general election

General elections were held in Costa Rica on 2 February 1996. The presidential election was won by former President Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen of the National Liberation Party, who defeated Rafael √Ångel Calder√≥n Fournier of the Social Christian Unity Party and Ott√≥n Sol√≠s of the Citizens' Action Party. Figueres's victory marked the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president's party had been re-elected.

## Background

The 1990 elections were an important turning point in Costa Rican politics, marking the first time in 17 years that the ruling National Liberation Party (PLN) was not re-elected. Rafael √Ångel Calder√≥n Fournier, who was elected president, was the first member of the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC) to win the presidency. The victory of the PUSC, which had been founded in 1983, was a major upset, given the PLN's long history of dominance in Costa Rican politics. The election was also significant because it was the first time that a party not affiliated with the PLN or the National Unification Party (PUN) had won the presidency.

The PUSC's victory was attributed to several factors, including voter dissatisfaction with the PLN's handling of the economy, corruption scandals, and the party's support for a market-oriented economic policy. The election was also notable for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot.

The 1990s were a period of significant political and economic change in Costa Rica. The country experienced a period of economic growth and development, but it was also marked by challenges such as debt reduction, privatization, and the impact of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). The 1990s also saw the consolidation of the PUSC as a major political force in Costa Rica, with the party winning several elections at the local and national levels.

The 1994 elections were marked by a close race between the PLN and the PUSC. The PLN's candidate, Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen, was defeated by the PUSC's Miguel √Ångel Rodr√≠guez, who won with 48.6% of the vote. The election was significant because it was the first time that a woman, Epsy Campbell Barr, was elected to the Legislative Assembly.

The 1996 elections were also significant for Costa Rican politics, as they saw the return of the PLN to power. Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen was elected president, marking the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president's party was re-elected. The election was also notable for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot. The 1990s were a period of significant political and economic change in Costa Rica, with the consolidation of the PUSC as a major political force and the PLN's return to power.

## Campaign

Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen was the candidate for the National Liberation Party (PLN) during the 1996 election. Figueres was the son of Jos√© Figueres Ferrer, a former president of Costa Rica and a prominent figure in the country's political history. He had previously served as a congressman and as a minister of the presidency during the administration of his father. Figueres was a member of the PLN and was known for his pro-business and center-left political views.

Ott√≥n Sol√≠s was the candidate for the Citizens' Action Party (PAC). Sol√≠s was a lawyer and economist who had previously served as a congressman and as minister of planning and economic policy. He was known for his environmentalist views and his opposition to privatization.

Rafael √Ångel Calder√≥n Fournier was the candidate for the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC). Calder√≥n was a member of the PUSC and was known for his conservative political views. He had previously served as a congressman and was a member of the Calder√≥n family, which has a long history in Costa Rican politics.

The 1996 election was a close race, with all three candidates receiving a significant portion of the vote. In the end, Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen was elected president, marking the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president's party was re-elected. The election was also significant for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot.

## Aftermath

The 1996 elections were a significant moment in Costa Rican politics, marking the return of the National Liberation Party (PLN) to power after a six-year hiatus. Jos√© Mar√≠a Figueres Olsen's victory was the first time since 1974 that an incumbent president's party was re-elected, and it was a significant boost for the PLN, which had been facing challenges from the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC).

The election was also notable for its high voter turnout, with 80.6% of eligible voters casting a ballot. This high turnout reflected a strong interest in the political process and a desire for change.

President Figueres's administration faced several challenges, including economic issues such as inflation and unemployment, as well as political scandals and corruption allegations. Despite these challenges, Figueres was able to implement some significant reforms, including changes to the tax system and public spending. He also focused on improving infrastructure and promoting tourism.

The 1990s were a period of significant political and economic change in Costa Rica. The country experienced a period of economic growth and development, but it was also marked by challenges such as debt reduction, privatization, and the impact of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). The 1990s also saw the consolidation of the Social Christian Unity Party (PUSC) as a major political force in Costa Rica, with the party winning several elections at the local and national levels.

Overall, the 1996 elections were a significant moment in Costa Rican politics, marking a change in leadership and a period of continued development for the country.

[{'content': "Prevedi naslednje angle≈°ko besedilo v sloven≈°ƒçino.\n# Asgar Zaheer\n\nAsgar Zaheer is a neuroscientist and retired Professor of Neurology at the University of Missouri at Columbia and the Emeritus Associate Professor at the University of Iowa. \n\nZaheer was previously a Research Career Scientist at the Department of Veterans Affairs for 33 years. His research examines the role of Glia Maturation Factor (GMF) in neuroinflammation and neurodegeneration, with a focus on mechanisms associated with Multiple Sclerosis (MS), Parkinson's disease (PD), Alzheimer's disease (AD) and Traumatic Brain Injury (TBI). He has published in journals including Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of USA, Journal of Biological Chemistry, Journal of Neurochemistry, Brain Research, Biochemistry, Brain, Behavior, and Immunity, and Frontiers in Neuroscience.\n\n## Education\n\nZaheer completed his Bachelor's degree at Marathwada University from 1966 to 1970 and pursued a Master's degree there from 1970 to 1972. He subsequently earned his Ph.D. in Biochemistry from Bombay University (Tata Memorial Hospital, Cancer Research Institute) between 1973 and 1979.\n\n## Career\n\nFrom 1979 to 1982, Zaheer served as a Postdoctoral Research Associate at the University of Iowa, progressing to roles such as Assistant Research Scientist from 1982 to 1987, Associate Research Scientist from 1987 to 1988, and Research Scientist from 1988 to 1995. In 1995, he was appointed Associate Director, a position he held until 2004, and Adjunct Assistant Professor, serving until 2005. He also assumed the role of Adjunct Assistant Professor of Surgery in 2003, continuing until 2006.\n\nIn 2005, Zaheer took on two concurrent roles: Assistant Professor of Neurology from 2005 to 2011 and Director of Neurochemistry from 2005 to 2016. Additionally, in 2010, he joined the graduate programs in Neuroscience and Bioscience, where he remained until 2016. He was promoted to Associate Professor in 2011, serving in this capacity until 2016. Since 2016, he has held the title of Emeritus Associate Professor.\n\nZaheer worked at the Veterans Affairs Health Care System, where he served as a Research Health Science Specialist from 1988 to 2016, and a Research Career Scientist at the Truman VA from 2016 to 2021. Furthermore, he was the Director of the VA Open Field Blast TBI Facility from 2018 to 2022. Simultaneously, he was a Professor and Director of the Center for Translational Neuroscience at the University of Missouri from 2016 to 2022.\n\n## Research\n\nZaheer, widely focused on the field of neuroscience, has worked on elucidating the role and mechanisms of Glia Maturation Factor (GMF) within the central nervous system, thereby contributing to the understanding of neurodegenerative diseases. His research findings about GMF, a protein that plays a key role in neuroinflammation, has contributed to the understanding of neurodegenerative diseases like Multiple Sclerosis (MS), Parkinson's (PD), Alzheimer's (AD), and Traumatic brain Injury (TBI). He has explored how an increased expression of GMF in cells can contribute to neuroinflammation, which in turn can activate pro-inflammatory gene expression, leading to neural damage and ultimately cause neuronal death.\n\nA considerable body of Zaheer's work has focused on understanding how GMF induction and activation in neuroglial cells contribute to the pathogenesis of brain disorders and injuries. \n\nThrough his research, he has identified GMF as a significant and less-explored factor impacting the progression of neurodegenerative diseases. Highlighting the role of GMF in neuroinflammation, his studies have explored how GMF exacerbates neuron damage in neurodegenerative diseases through promoting oxidative stress and apoptosis, the process of programmed cell death that can lead to neurodegeneration. His work has also identified GMF as a modulator of various signaling pathways in the brain, thereby presenting opportunities for therapeutic intervention. Favorably modulating GMF activity or inhibiting its overexpression could potentially alleviate symptoms or slow the progression of various neurodegenerative disorders.\n\nZaheer has made contributions to other aspects of neuroscience, particularly his work related to the molecular and cellular mechanisms underlying brain injuries. \\\n\n## Awards and honors\n \n\n* 1995 ‚Äì Special Contribution Award, Department of Veterans Affairs\n\n* 2004-2007, 2008-2012, 2014-2018 ‚Äì VA Merit Review Award, Department of Veterans Affairs\n\n* 2004-2009, 2009-2013, 2011-2016 ‚Äì NIH RO1 Award, National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke\n\n* 2015-2020 ‚Äì NIH RO1 Award, National Institute of Aging\n\n## Selected articles\n\n* Lim, R., Miller, J. F., & Zaheer, A. (1989). Purification and characterization of glia maturation factor beta: a growth regulator for neurons and glia. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 86(10), 3901-3905.\n\n* Thangavel, R., Van Hoesen, G. W., & Zaheer, A. (2008). Posterior parahippocampal gyrus pathology in Alzheimer's disease. Neuroscience, 154(2), 667-676.\n\n* Zaheer, S., Wu, Y., Sahu, S. K., & Zaheer, A. (2010). Overexpression of glia maturation factor reinstates susceptibility to myelin oligodendrocyte glycoprotein-induced experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis in glia maturation factor deficient mice. Neurobiology of disease, 40(3), 593-598.\n\n* Kempuraj, D., Khan, M. M., Thangavel, R., Xiong, Z., Yang, E., & Zaheer, A. (2013). Glia maturation factor induces interleukin-33 release from astrocytes: implications for neurodegenerative diseases. Journal of Neuroimmune Pharmacology, 8, 643-650.\n\n* Khan, M. M., Zaheer, S., Nehman, J., & Zaheer, A. (2014). Suppression of glia maturation factor expression prevents 1-methyl-4-phenylpyridinium (MPP+)-induced loss of mesencephalic dopaminergic neurons. Neuroscience, 277, 196-205.\n\n* Raikwar, S. P., Thangavel, R., Dubova, I., Selvakumar, G. P., Ahmed, M. E., Kempuraj, D., ... & Zaheer, A. (2019). Targeted gene editing of glia maturation factor in microglia: a novel Alzheimer‚Äôs disease therapeutic target. Molecular neurobiology, 56, 378-393.\n\n* Ahmed, M. E., Selvakumar, G. P., Kempuraj, D., Raikwar, S. P., Thangavel, R., Bazley, K., ... & Zaheer, A. (2020). Glia maturation factor (GMF) regulates microglial expression phenotypes and the associated neurological deficits in a mouse model of traumatic brain injury. Molecular Neurobiology, 57(11), 4438-4450.\n\n* Selvakumar, G. P., Ahmed, M. E., Iyer, S. S., Thangavel, R., Kempuraj, D., Raikwar, S. P., ... & Zaheer, A. (2020). Absence of glia maturation factor protects from axonal injury and motor behavioral impairments after traumatic brain injury. Experimental neurobiology, 29(3), 230.\n\n## References\n\nIndian neuroscientists\nIndian academics\nDr. Babasaheb Ambedkar Marathwada University alumni\nUniversity of Mumbai alumni\nUniversity of Iowa faculty\nUniversity of Missouri faculty\nLiving people", 'role': 'user'}]

His research findings about GMF, a protein that plays a key role in neuroinflammation, has contributed to the understanding of neurodegenerative diseases like Multiple Sclerosis (MS), Parkinson's (PD), Alzheimer's (AD), and Traumatic brain Injury (TBI). He has explored how an increased expression of GMF in cells can contribute to neuroinflammation, which in turn can activate pro-inflammatory gene expression, leading to neural damage and ultimately cause neuronal death.\n\nA considerable body of Zaheer's work has focused on understanding how GMF induction and activation in neuroglial cells contribute to the pathogenesis of brain disorders and injuries. \n\nThrough his research, he has identified GMF as a significant and less-explored factor impacting the progression of neurodegenerative diseases. Highlighting the role of GMF in neuroinflammation, his studies have explored how GMF exacerbates neuron damage in neurodegenerative diseases through promoting oxidative stress and apoptosis, the process of programmed cell death that can lead to neurodegeneration. His work has also identified GMF as a modulator of various signaling pathways in the brain, thereby presenting opportunities for therapeutic intervention. Favorably modulating GMF activity or inhibiting its overexpression could potentially alleviate symptoms or slow the progression of various neurodegenerative disorders.\n\nZaheer has made contributions to other aspects of neuroscience, particularly his work related to the molecular and cellular mechanisms underlying brain injuries. \\\n\n## Awards and honors\n \n\n* 1995 ‚Äì Special Contribution Award, Department of Veterans Affairs\n\n* 2004-2007, 2008-2012, 2014-2018 ‚Äì VA Merit Review Award, Department of Veterans Affairs\n\n* 2004-2009, 2009-2013, 2011-2016 ‚Äì NIH RO1 Award, National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke\n\n* 2015-2020 ‚Äì NIH RO1 Award, National Institute of Aging\n\n## Selected articles\n\n* Lim, R., Miller, J. prompt_logprobs=None, outputs=[CompletionOutput(index=0, text="# Gyeongju National Museum\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum () is a national museum in Gyeongju, South Korea. It is one of the largest and most visited museums in the country. The museum is located in the city center, near the historic site of Daereungwon. It opened in 1972 and was renovated in 2006. The museum's collection consists of 18,555 items, with 15,427 of them on display.\n\n## History\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum was opened on April 15, 1972. The museum was originally constructed with a floor area of 2,826 square meters and a total building area of 5,151 square meters. The museum was built close to the Daereungwon tumuli complex, a major archaeological site.\n\nIn 1975, the museum was designated as a national museum. On July 23, 2006, the museum was renovated and reopened. The new building was designed by architect Kim Jong-seop and has a floor area of 22,161 square meters and a total building area of 27,609 square meters. The museum is located in the city center, near the historic site of Daereungwon.\n\n## Collection\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum has a collection of 18,555 items, with 15,427 of them on display. The museum's collection includes a variety of artifacts from the Silla period (57 BCE ‚Äì 935 CE), including gold crowns, beaded belts, and burial objects. The museum also has a collection of artifacts from the Three Kingdoms of Korea, as well as from the Goryeo and Joseon periods.\n\nThe museum's collection is divided into several categories, including:\n\n* Archaeology: The museum has a large collection of artifacts from the Three Kingdoms of Korea, including pottery, bronzeware, and ironware.\n\n* Art: The museum has a collection of paintings, calligraphy, and sculptures from the Goryeo and Joseon periods.\n\n* History: The museum has a collection of documents, photographs, and other materials related to the history of Gyeongju.\n\n* Education: The museum offers a variety of educational programs, including lectures, workshops, and guided tours.\n\n## Exhibitions\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum offers a variety of exhibitions, including:\n\n* Permanent exhibitions: The museum has several permanent exhibitions that showcase its collection of artifacts from the Three Kingdoms of Korea, the Goryeo and Joseon periods, and the modern era.\n\n* Special exhibitions: The museum also offers special exhibitions that showcase the work of contemporary artists and the results of archaeological excavations.\n\n* Educational programs: The museum offers a variety of educational programs, including lectures, workshops, and guided tours.\n\n## Architecture\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum was designed by architect Kim Jong-seop. The museum's design is meant to be in harmony with the surrounding environment and the historic site of Daereungwon. The museum's exterior is made of glass and steel, and the interior is designed to be open and airy.\n\nThe museum's main entrance is a large, glass-covered atrium that is open to the sky. The atrium is surrounded by a series of galleries that are arranged in a semi-circular shape. The galleries are connected by a series of bridges and walkways.\n\n## Impact\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum is one of the most popular tourist destinations in Gyeongju. The museum attracts visitors from all over the world who come to see its collection of artifacts and to learn about the history of Gyeongju. The museum is also an important cultural and educational institution in Gyeongju, offering a variety of programs and exhibitions that promote the city's rich history and culture.\n\n## Criticism\n\nThe Gyeongju National Museum has been criticized for its treatment of artifacts and for its role in the repatriation of Korean cultural property.\n\nIn 2013, the museum was criticized for its handling of the Gyeongju Gold Crown. The crown, which is one of the most important artifacts in the museum's collection, was found to have been damaged by improper storage and handling. The museum was criticized for not taking better care of the crown and for not informing the public about the damage.\n\nIn 2015, the museum was criticized for its role in the repatriation of Korean cultural property. The museum was accused of not doing enough to repatriate artifacts that had been illegally exported from Korea. The museum was also criticized for not doing enough to educate the public about the importance of repatriating cultural property.\n\n## See also\n\n* List of museums in South Korea\n\n* List of museums in Gyeongju\n\n## Further reading\n\n* Gyeongju National Museum.
