He later completed his PhD at the Department of Mathematics of Mons University, focusing on computational complexity in cluster analysis within Euclidean spaces.\n\n## Achievements\n\nLehert is an Honorary Professor at the School of Management, Louvain University, Belgium, and the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Melbourne, Australia. He has also served as a statistical adviser for the United Nations and a member of the Belgian Board of Statistics.\n\nHis research includes the development of statistical techniques for evaluating the long-term effects of anti-diabetic drugs and methods for randomized trials in addiction, psychiatric disorders, and cardiovascular diseases. He contributed to structural equation modeling to assess the impact of lifestyle on aging, including menopausal effects on mood and bone loss.\n\nIn the field of Assisted Reproductive Technology (ART), Lehert developed predictive models for IVF success and outcomes for poor ovarian responders.\n\n## References\n\n1949 births\nLiving people\n21st-century Belgian scientists', 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # 2009‚Äì10 South Alabama Jaguars men's basketball team

The 2009‚Äì10 South Alabama Jaguars men's basketball team represented the University of South Alabama during the 2009‚Äì10 NCAA Division I men's basketball season. The Jaguars, led by 10th year head coach Ronnie Arrow, played their home games at the Mitchell Center and were members of the West Division of the Sun Belt Conference. They finished the season 14‚Äì17 overall, 10‚Äì8 in Sun Belt play.

## Previous season

The Jaguars finished the 2008‚Äì09 season 12‚Äì16 overall, 7‚Äì11 in Sun Belt play. They lost in the first round of the Sun Belt tournament to Florida Atlantic.

More specifically, Dehan speakers \nare mainly found in ten villages in the eastern part of Barak river namely Horinagar, Japirbon, Leburbon, Gororbon, Dewan (Labok) or Dewan Bosti, Narayanpur, Larchingpar, Thaligram, Lakkhichora, and Digli. Though Dehan speakers are located in the same district, however, they are scattered in different places. Out of ten villages, Japirbon is the \nbiggest and the populous one.\n\nOther than Assamese, Dehan shares its lexical items and linguistic features with Sylheti and Bishnupriya Manipuri as well, which is due to long language contact apart from being closely related. Dehan is closely related to the Kamrupi and Standard dialects of Assamese.\n\n## History\n\nAmong the communities of Barak valley, the Dehans are one of the early settlers as their settlement dates back to 16th century. They are migrants from Brahmaputra valley. They entered Cachar during Chilarai‚Äôs conquest of Cachar plains, but some of them didn't return to Brahmaputra valley and made Cachar their permanent home. Chilarai campaigned through Maibong, Manipur, Jaintia, Srihatta and Tripura and finally the plains of Cachar were annexed to the Koch kingdom in 1562. Later the Koch principality in Cachar was reduced to a small zamindari in and around Khaspur.\n\nThe Koch-Rajbongshis of Barak valley are better known as Dehans. They initially had their settlements around Khaspur but later, owning to different socio-political compulsions, they had to branch off to different villages.\n\n## Reference\n\n* \n\n* \n\n* \n\n* \n\n* \n\nEastern Indo-Aryan languages\nLanguages of Assam\nAssamese language", 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # 1995 U.S. Figure Skating Championships

The 1995 U.S. Figure Skating Championships took place from January 10 to 15, 1995 at the Providence Civic Center in Providence, Rhode Island. Medals were awarded in men's singles, ladies' singles, pair skating, and ice dancing. The senior competitions determined the U.S. team for the 1995 World Championships.

## Men

The men's short program was held on January 12 and the free skating on January 14.

Judges:

* Patricia Macfarlane

* Janice B. Robinson

* Jeannette D. Burns

* John Nicks

* Ellen Burka

* Sheri G. McCourt

* Jaycie A. Smith

* Paul K. Baker

* Tatjana Danilenko

## Ladies

The ladies' short program was held on January 12 and the free skating on January 14.

Judges:

* Tatjana Danilenko

* Patricia Macfarlane

* John Nicks

* Ellen Burka

* Janice B. Robinson

* Jeannette D. Burns

* Jaycie A. Smith

* Paul K. Baker

* Sheri G. McCourt

## Pairs

The pairs' short program was held on January 13 and the free skating on January 15.

Judges:

* Patricia Macfarlane

* Janice B. Robinson

* Jeannette D. Burns

* John Nicks

* Ellen Burka

* Sheri G. McCourt

* Jaycie A. Smith

* Paul K. Baker

* Tatjana Danilenko

## Ice dancing

The ice dancing compulsory dances were held on January 10 and the original and free dances on January 12.

Judges:

* Patricia Macfarlane

* Janice B. Robinson

* Jeannette D. Burns

* John Nicks

* Ellen Burka

* Sheri G. McCourt

* Jaycie A. Smith

* Paul K. Baker

* Tatjana Danilenko

U.S. Figure Skating Championships

On the obverse side of the pendant is an outline of the borders of the State of Texas, with the words, "TEXAS STATE GUARD" on the upper three sides of the octagon and "ACHIEVEMENT" along the lower three sides of the octagon. The word ‚ÄúACHIEVEMENT‚Äù is bookended by a waterdrop with point facing upwards, atop a circle, atop a waterdrop with points towards the word ‚ÄúACHIEVEMENT‚Äù. On the reverse side of the pendant is a five-pointed raised star, one point up, 3/8 of an inch in diameter surrounded by a wreath formed by an olive branch on the right and a live oak branch on the left, surrounded by the words "TEXAS STATE GUARD" along the upper three sides of the octagon and "TEXANS SERVING TEXANS" along the lower three sides of the octagon, in raised letters.\n\n## Ribbon\n\nThe pendant is suspended by a ring from a rayon moir√© ribbon 1-3/8 inches long 1-3/8 inches and wide, composed of three vertical stripes of Bluebird #67117 (9/16 inch), Ultramarine #67118 (1/4 inch), and Bluebird #67117 (9/16 inch).\n\n## Devices\n\nA bronze oak leaf cluster award device is conferred for second and succeeding decorations. Translation: # 1962‚Äì63 Hellenic Football League

The 1962‚Äì63 Hellenic Football League season was the 17th in the history of the Hellenic Football League, a football competition in England.

## Premier Division

The Premier Division featured 12 clubs which competed in the previous season, along with three new clubs:

* Abingdon Town, promoted from Division One

* Banbury Spencer, promoted from Division One

* Newbury, promoted from Division One

## Division One

Division One featured 12 clubs which competed in the previous season, along with three new clubs:

* Abingdon Town Reserves, reserve team of Abingdon Town

* Carterton, joined from the Oxfordshire Senior League

* Witney Town, joined from the Oxfordshire Senior League

## Division Two

Division Two featured 10 clubs which competed in the previous season, along with four new clubs:

* Old Woodstock Town, joined from the Oxfordshire Senior League

* Wantage Town, joined from the Oxfordshire Senior League

* Wheatley United, joined from the Oxfordshire Senior League

* Witney Town Reserves, reserve team of Witney Town

## Cup results

* Hellenic League Cup - Abingdon Town 2‚Äì0 Banbury United

* Berks & Bucks Senior Cup - Slough Town 1‚Äì0 Headington Amateurs

* Berks & Bucks Intermediate Cup - Newbury 2‚Äì1 Flackwell Heath

* Berks & Bucks Junior Cup - Burnham 2‚Äì1 Flackwell Heath

## Football League applications

No Hellenic League club applied for election to the Football League this season.

## Thames Valley Cup

The Thames Valley Cup was a knockout competition for clubs in the area covered by the three regional football associations, the Berks & Bucks FA, the Oxfordshire FA and the Wiltshire FA.

This season, the competition featured 17 clubs from the Hellenic League, 13 from the Spartan League and 8 from the Wiltshire League.

## First round

The first round featured 20 of the 21 Hellenic League clubs, with the exception of Abingdon Town.

## Semi-finals

* Burnham 1‚Äì0 Flackwell Heath, Hellenic League

* Didcot Town 2‚Äì0 Newbury, Hellenic League

## Final

Ties were played at the home ground of the club with the higher league status.

## References

1962-63

Korea had ended its period of isolation several decades before, after it was forcefully opened by Japan. The Korean government leased a significant portion of land north of Namsan, free of charge, to the Japanese residents for the construction of the park. Construction began on it in either 1908 or 1909, and the park officially opened on May 29, 1910. The former Korean monarch Gojong (whom had been forced to abdicate in lieu of his son) selected the name of the park. Its opening ceremony was attended by around 2,000 people. To commemorate the park's opening, he personally engraved the name of the park on a stone monument; this monument was erected at the entrance to the park in 1912. It is not known whether Gojong had performed this engraving by choice. Months after the opening of the park, Japan formally annexed Korea.\n\nOn July 18, 1919, it was decided that the park would be closed to make way for Ch≈çsen Shrine, which was to be the main Shinto shrine in Korea. Its facilities were almost all destroyed during the construction process. The park was still attested to in a 1928 listing of parks in the city. However, it was not listed in a 1940 listing.\n\n## Stone monument\n\nThe stone monument was moved elsewhere during the demolition process. It eventually ended up around the entrance of what would become Namsan Tunnel No. 3. During the tunnel construction process, it was possibly moved again to another resting point nearby. In 2002, it was discovered lying in the grass behind a fence. In 2009, it was restored and made into a public exhibit.\n\nThe stone monument is of size . It was placed on a granite pedestal of the dimensions . On the front is inscribed the name of the park in Hanja. It had an inscription on the back; by the time of its rediscovery, the inscription was nearly illegible. Its message is now known from old photographs. Three square stone pillars surrounded the monument. There are possibly bullet marks in the stone; these may be from the 1950‚Äì1953 Korean War.\n\nThe monument has been described as an unpleasant but important reminder of the colonial period. It is not classified in South Korea's national heritage system; instead it was given the Seoul Future Heritage designation, which is administered by the Seoul Metropolitan Government. This is reflective of the monument's association with a Japanese institution in the country. In 2017, the monument became one stop along the Trail of National Humiliation, which walks between various former sites of Japanese institutions near Namsan.\n\n## External links\n\n1910 establishments in Korea\nKeij≈ç\n1910s disestablishments in Korea\nNamsan", 'role': 'user'}]

Translation: # 2021‚Äì22 Burton Albion F.C. season

The 2021‚Äì22 season was the 128th season in the existence of Burton Albion Football Club and the club's fourth consecutive season in League One. In addition to the league, they also competed in the 2021‚Äì22 FA Cup, the 2021‚Äì22 EFL Cup and the 2021‚Äì22 EFL Trophy.

## Pre-season

The Brewers announced their first pre-season friendly on 4 June 2021, with a trip to face Championship side Derby County. A second friendly was added on 11 June, a home game against Loughborough University. On 16 June, Albion announced a third pre-season friendly, a trip to face National League side Notts County. A fourth friendly was added on 21 June, against Championship side Stoke City. A fifth and final friendly was announced on 29 June, a home game against Premier League side Watford.

## Matches

On Thursday, 17 June, the league fixtures were announced.

## FA Cup

The first round draw was made on 25 October, with Burton being drawn at home to fellow League One side Gillingham. The draw for the second round was made on 8 November, with the Brewers being drawn at home to league rivals Fleetwood Town.

## EFL Cup

The first round draw was made on 24 June, with Burton being drawn at home to Championship side Stoke City.

## EFL Trophy

On 20 July 2021, the group stage draw was made, with Burton being placed in Northern Group F alongside Aston Villa U21, Derby County and Mansfield Town.

Translation: # Alan Clarke (footballer, born 1939)

Alan Clarke (born 10 January 1939) is an English former professional footballer who played as a winger.

## Career

Born in Sunderland, Clarke began his career with his hometown club Sunderland, where he made 33 appearances in the Football League. He signed for Huddersfield Town in 1960, and went on to make over 400 appearances for the club in all competitions, scoring 116 goals. He helped Huddersfield win the Third Division title in 1969‚Äì70, and was the club's top scorer in the 1963‚Äì64 season. Clarke was released by Huddersfield in 1970, and he subsequently played for non-league clubs Blyth Spartans and Dunston UTS.

## Personal life

Clarke is the younger brother of fellow footballer Joe Clarke, and the uncle of footballer Martin Clarke. He is also the father of footballer Paul Clarke.
